<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 15:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Dip: Down Ends Off 13.04 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell Monday, forcing investors to  
contend with the possibility that the Dow Jones industrial average 
might not close above 10,000 any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable TV and Internet stocks provided some upward momentum to  
the technology sector. But personal computer shares sold off, 
leaving the Nasdaq composite down 25.33 at 2,395.94 and the 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index off 2.28 at 1,297.01. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow index crossed 10,000 several times last week in intraday  
trading. On Monday it failed even to do that, meandering throughout 
the session and ending 13.04 lower at 9,890.51. The Dow is still up 
more than 8 percent so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward M. Kerschner, stock market strategist at PaineWebber,  
said that unless interest rates move meaningfully lower or 1999 
earnings growth is significantly higher than current forecasts of 5 
percent to 8 percent, ``expect -- in the best case -- to see the 
market stall around these levels for a good few months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no economic news to influence trading today. Interest  
rates edged higher in the bond market, reversing an earlier 
decline. The yield on 30-year Treasury bonds closed at 5.57 
percent, up from 5.55 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But cable TV stocks rose on takeover news. MediaOne rose 7 3/4 to  
68 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange after Comcast offered to buy it 
for $44.3 billion. Comcast's Series A shares lost 6 1/2 to 66 3/8 in 
Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet shares also continued to blaze higher, with America  
Online gaining 10 3/4 to 130 on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Personal computer stocks were weaker after Donaldson, Lufkin and  
Jenrette Securities analyst Kevin McCarthy lowered his earnings 
estimate on Dell Computer and said he expects the PC industry to 
grow only 8 percent in 1999. That is down from his previous 
estimate of 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer shares slipped 2 3/8 to 37 7/8.  
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street has been jittery for weeks about the health of the  
computer market. On Friday, IBM led the Dow industrials lower after 
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's Thomas Kraemer issued a word of 
caution about the computer maker. On Monday, BancBoston Robertson 
Stephens &AMP; Co.'s Dan Niles followed suit, and IBM's shares fell 1 5/8 
to 167. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were largely responsible for leading the  
market out of its autumn slump, said Tony Dwyer, chief equity 
strategist at Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; Co. It is crucial that they 
begin to perform better if the market is to continue to improve. 
That isn't likely, given the extremely high prices on technology 
stocks, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're an index watcher, and you're watching the Dow 30  
stocks, you've got to be bullish,'' Dwyer said. ``But if you're an 
investment adviser, you have to look at everything, not just 30 
stocks. And if you're looking at the broader market, you've got to 
sell it right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume totaled 824 
million shares, down from the 1.08 billion on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.19 to 610.49, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.49 to 717.36. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.38 to 393.20. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas trading, the Japanese stock market was closed for a  
holiday. The DAX index in Frankfurt skidded 1.42 percent, as 
government crises both domestically and on the European Union 
level, as well as uncertainty over the Kosovo conflict, made 
investors wary. The FT-SE 100 index in London eased 0.17 percent, 
and the CAC in Paris gave up 0.54 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
