<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 07:23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rodman Says He's Back for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Dennis Rodman offered only his word that  
whatever prompted him to leave the Los Angeles Lakers is resolved 
for now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing's ever ironed out. They just kind of subside for a  
while,'' he said Sunday after ending a self-imposed layoff to 
address personal issues that kept him from the team for eight days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be here the rest of the season. I've used up my hall  
pass,'' he said, adding that his return got just the kind of 
reaction from his teammates that he anticipated -- none. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't expecting these guys to come over and shake my hand  
... or anything like that. I expected the team to go on as though 
nothing happened. So, that's what we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman played 23 minutes and had four points and six rebounds to  
help the Lakers, who he says fined him $100 per day, beat the 
Orlando Magic 115-104. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-time rebounding champion left the Lakers after  
practice March 13, telling coach Kurt Rambis he needed time to 
resolve personal matters. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed the first four games of a six-game road trip, and the  
Lakers lost three of them after going 9-0 with him in the lineup. 
He said he hadn't given much thought to the team being unbeaten 
when he plays. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's good that we won (Sunday),'' he said. ``That way I  
don't have to answer all the critics tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman insisted leaving the team had nothing to do with  
drinking, gambling or marital problems. Instead, he said he was 
sorting out whether he wanted to continue playing basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	He confirmed spending part of the layoff gambling in Las Vegas.  
He shrugged off a suggestion that that seemed like an odd way to 
confront issues bothering him. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's me. A lot of people go to Cancun or Hawaii ... I'm  
different. I do it my way,'' he said, adding that he gave 
retirement serious consideration before wife Carmen Electra 
convinced him to get back to work. 
</P>
<P>
	``This game ain't worth that much for me to lose who I am ... I  
would have stayed out. I probably would have gotten kicked out of 
the state of California. But it doesn't matter. I have to keep my 
head and my life together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old forward, who's played on five NBA championship  
teams, did not apologize -- publicly, or to his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't need to do that. I won't do that,'' Rodman said.  
``Like I said, action speaks louder than words. I came back ... 
People have to understand this is me. Just let me do what I've got 
to do and everything will be all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates were supportive.  
</P>
<P>
	``He had personal problems and our organization was gracious  
enough to let him go to Vegas and do some gambling and clear his 
head, whatever,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``But he's back. We all 
said what we had to say to him. Hopefully, he doesn't do that 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 10 games, Rodman has averaged 2.1 points and 9.9 minutes  
while playing about 24 minutes per outing. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can grab a stat sheet, and what he brings won't show up,''  
teammate Derek Harper said. ``But his energy and his knowledge of 
the game, his defensive ability, his rebounding ability, it helps 
our basketball team. Hopefully, he's going to be here the rest of 
the season. That's what I hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman arrived in town at about 3 a.m. and rode the team bus to  
Orlando Arena where he spoke briefly with Rambis before heading to 
the opposing locker room to meet with the Magic's Chuck Daly, who 
coached Rodman in Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just asked him if he was all right,'' Rambis said. ``He said  
he was all right, and that was it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if Rodman assured him he will not leave the team  
again, the coach said: ``I don't think anybody can make those 
assurances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis became coach on Feb. 26, the same day Rodman first played  
for the Lakers. He declined to speculate on what might happen if 
the forward leaves the team again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to cross that bridge if and when it happens,''  
Rambis said. ``I'm not going to sit here with hard and fast rules 
to what happens in future situations.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
