<DOCNO> APW19990322.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Interest Rates Fall / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities fell in Monday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $6.5 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.375 percent, down from 4.470 percent last 
week. An additional $7.51 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.420 percent, down from 4.530 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the lowest since Jan. 25, when the  
bills sold at a rate of 4.305 percent. The six-month rate was the 
lowest since Feb. 1, when the rate was 4.390 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.498 percent for three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,889.40, and 4.597 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,776.50. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 4.74 
percent last week from 4.77 percent the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
