<DOCNO> APW19990322.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Break-Ins Point to Bombing Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANDREWS, N.C. (AP) -- Bombing suspect Eric Robert Rudolph may be  
the intruder who broke into up to 12 mountain homes from July to 
January to steal food and toilet paper or sometimes just to get a 
shower and a shave, a federal agent said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The break-ins were very similar and occurred in a defined area,  
said Woody Enderson of the Southeast Bomb Task Force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do feel they are a strong indication of his presence,'' he  
said, despite the absence of hair or other evidence that might 
specifically link the break-ins to Rudolph. 
</P>
<P>
	The break-ins have happened since July, the last confirmed  
sighting of Rudolph, Enderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	He described the break-ins as very significant in the hunt for  
Rudolph, the suspect in a fatal Birmingham, Ala., abortion clinic 
bombing last year and others in Atlanta, including the 1996 Olympic 
Park bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally, someone wouldn't go into someone's house to take a  
shower and shave,'' Enderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the leads, Enderson and other members of the task force  
announced a reduction in the number of agents involved in the 
search in the Nantahala Forest in western North Carolina. He did 
not give specifics on the reduction but said it had been planned 
for several months. 
</P>
<P>
	Enderson reiterated a long-standing belief by members of the  
task force that all of their leads indicate that Rudolph is still 
in the area and that he is not receiving any help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 13:45:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxing Judge Had Been Fired Before </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The judge at the center of the dispute surrounding  
the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis draw was dismissed by another 
boxing organization a year ago for being ``a loner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jon Robinson, president of the fringe World Boxing Union, said  
he had no problems with the way Eugenia Williams scored bouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We consider the WBU to be a family and Eugenia Williams didn't  
fit in,'' he said. ``She was a loner and not a team player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, reached at her city hall office in Atlantic City,  
N.J., where is she is a clerk, refused to take a call from The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, appointed by the IBF for Lewis-Holyfield bout, has  
appeared before a New York state Senate hearing concerning her role 
in the fight at Madison Square Garden on March 13. 
</P>
<P>
	She judged the fight 115-113 in favor of Holyfield. However,  
after watching a replay, she said she would have scored it 
differently had photographers not impeded her view. 
</P>
<P>
	English judge Larry O'Connell scored it 115-115, while South  
African judge Stan Christodoulou favored Lewis, 116-113. 
</P>
<P>
	The WBU, headquartered in Britain, dismissed 30 judges last year  
and Williams was among them. She has been a judge 10 years. 
Robinson said she worked at about one championship fight per year 
for the WBU for four or five years. 
</P>
<P>
	In another matter, the WBU said that starting April 1, judges at  
its championship bouts will score on a 20-point system instead of 
the current 10-point system. Robinson said the 20-point system 
would allow greater flexibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 16:52:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky's Book Tour Draws Hundreds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Admirers said they wanted a page of history.  
Collectors hunted for an autograph. Critics scoffed at the 
spectacle. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds turned out Monday for Monica Lewinsky's first -- and  
perhaps only -- stop in the United States to promote her biography 
``Monica's Story.'' Some arrived as early as 7 a.m., milling in a 
line that stretched into the street outside the bookstore. 
</P>
<P>
	The former White House intern, a Los Angeles native, arrived an  
hour late for the 12:30 p.m. signing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Monica looked strong, confident and in charge,'' said  
Elizabeth Jewels, who took an afternoon break from work to get her 
copy of the book signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the media, only photographers and cameramen were allowed  
inside -- briefly and only a handful at a time. Other journalists 
were barred from entering Brentano's Bookstore. Ms. Lewinsky was 
cordoned off at the back of the store, hidden from onlookers 
outside. 
</P>
<P>
	For those who managed to enter, the posted guidelines were  
clear: ``Absolutely no memorabilia, no photographs posed or 
otherwise.'' A book receipt was required, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd inside was respectful, unlike stops she made on a book  
tour in England and Scotland, where she was greeted by placards 
bearing such messages as ``Take her back, Bill.'' The only sign 
Monday read: ``Monica Rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all of the onlookers were admirers, though.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's hysterical not historical,'' said Herb Zoolman of  
Woodland Hills. ``I wouldn't want to help make her rich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some were taken aback by the commotion generated by the signing,  
which promoters touted as Lewinsky's only appearance in the United 
States. She was expected to return to Britain to resume her 19-stop 
book tour there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get this,'' said Taly Boczan, a 20-year-old literature  
major at the University of California, Santa Cruz, who was having 
lunch nearby. ``This is so bizarre.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, she added, ``You can't pass up the opportunity to see  
Monica Lewinsky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many saw Lewinsky Sunday night, when she turned out for the  
annual Vanity Fair post-Oscar fest at Morton's. She mugged for 
cameras before disappearing inside the fern-laden Melrose Avenue 
eatery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 05:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Oscar Parties Rage Into Wee Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- After a long Oscars ceremony, they  
partied like it's 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Winners, losers, also-rans. Famous, infamous, unknowns. They  
vamped, got kissy-faced and celebrated at post-Oscar parties raging 
into the wee hours today. 
</P>
<P>
	After the official academy Governors Ball at the downtown Los  
Angeles Music Center, limousines fanned out across Southern 
California. Many headed to West Hollywood, the most popular 
destination with six major bashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Best-director Steven Spielberg his ``Saving Private Ryan'' star  
Tom Hanks showed up at the DreamWorks-Paramount party at Barnaby's, 
where guests dined on raw oysters, shiitake mushroom pizza and 
chicken pot pie. 
</P>
<P>
	Handshaking. Hugs. Air kisses. Make that big wet kisses from  
Italy's ``Life is Beautiful'' Oscar-winner Roberto Benigni. 
</P>
<P>
	There was head-shaking, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Monica Lewinsky, shrouded in a black gown, showed up at Morton's  
for the annual Vanity Fair fest. She mugged for cameras before 
disappearing inside the fern-laden Melrose Avenue eatery. 
</P>
<P>
	The former White House intern was still inside when Jay Leno,  
king of the Lewinsky jokesters, strolled past the giant Oscar 
topiary at the Morton's entrance and went inside. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't known if Leno encountered Ms. Lewinsky, but actress  
Uma Thurman could be seen talking to her at one point. 
</P>
<P>
	It was an eclectic crowd: Madonna dancing with Ricky Martin,  
Edward Burns of ``Saving Private Ryan'' arm-in-arm with actress 
Heather Graham and ``Sling Blade'' star Dwight Yoakam with actress 
Bridget Fonda. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Hopkins, Jim Carrey, Ben Affleck, Matt Damon, Steve  
Martin, Tim Allen, Willem Dafoe, Mariah Carey were all there. 
Steven Baldwin -- blond hair slicked-back, wearing black leather 
pants and an ankle-length overcoat -- also showed up. So did Ed 
McMahon. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only party we're going to go to. We're not into  
this kind of stuff that much,'' McMahon said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Pagani, Elton John was holding court in a purple Versace  
suit. His annual AIDS bash raises more than $300,000 and partygoers 
included Janet Jackson, Rod Stewart and Leann Rimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Just up the street on Sunset Boulevard, the online Hollywood  
Stock Exchange and Excite! gathering dubbed Rock the Oscars 
featured a performance by Beck on the House of Blues stage. The 
computer-equipped party, described as a ``convergence of the 
digital world and Hollywood,'' allowed Internet users to contact 
partygoers online. 
</P>
<P>
	The pink and posh Beverly Hills Hotel hosted the Night of 100  
Stars party to raise money for Martin Scorsese's film preservation 
foundation. Ernest Borgnine, Elliot Gould, Tony Curtis and Rod 
Steiger were among those invited. 
</P>
<P>
	When the curtain came down on the 71st annual Academy Awards, a  
fleet of stretch limousines were idling outside. But departures 
were delayed for the obligatory rounds at the Governors Ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Call it networking: Lots of let's-do-lunch and  
have-your-people-call-my-people banter. Governors Ball guests were 
greeted by the sounds of a string band, appropriate considering the 
age of the majority of the guests. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those inside was 89-year-old director Elia Kazan, whose  
lifetime achievement award created a stir in Hollywood. Sitting at 
a table with Karl Malden, Kazan said: ``I'm glad it's over, but it 
was a nice evening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among Oscar winners making the rounds of the ball were Benigni,  
James Coburn, Judi Dench and Gwyneth Paltrow. But most of the stars 
were boarding limos an hour later to hit other parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 05:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
