<DOCNO> APW19990322.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:55:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Extend Gains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures extended their gains Monday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange as a group that controls two-thirds of the 
world's oil supply closed in on a new agreement to reduce output. 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil, unleaded gasoline and natural gas futures also  
moved sharply higher. On other commodity markets, soybeans and corn 
rose sharply, as did copper. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude rose as the 11-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting  
Countries were set to meet Tuesday in Vienna to formally ratify a 
plan that beginning in April would slash some 2 million barrels 
daily from world production in a bid to shore up prices. Crude 
until recently had been hovering at 12-year lows because of 
oversupply and a global economic crisis that sapped demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia, another major producer that is not a member of the  
group, also planned to cut 100,000 barrels from its production over 
the next three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Those agreements in the past week have led to a sharp increase  
in futures prices and prices at the pump, but they could be 
short-lived as investors await clear indications of whether the 
cuts are actually being made. There is still disagreement about 
whether oil producing nations have slashed the promised 3.23 
million barrels daily from production that they agreed to at this 
time last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for April delivery rose 26 cents to $15.50 a  
barrel; April heating oil rose 1.70 cents to 42.39 cents a gallon; 
April unleaded gasoline rose 1.78 cents to 49.42 cents a gallon; 
April natural gas rose 7 cents to $1.769 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans led sharp gains on the Chicago Board of Trade amid  
speculation the U.S. Agriculture Department might announce it 
planned another donation to cash-strapped Russia, with soybean meal 
or oil as the centerpiece of that package. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said after a meeting with  
Russian officials that they had requested more food aid this year 
and that the U.S. agency would consider that request. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is under pressure to boost exports as  
the trade deficit grows and farmers suffer from weak sales because 
of a global economic crisis. That has led to increased food 
donations to economically depressed countries and more 
government-backed loan and credit guarantees. 
</P>
<P>
	May soybeans rose 10 cents to $4.99 1/4 a bushel; May corn rose 3 1/4  
cents to $2.32 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures jumped on the New York Mercantile Exchange as  
supplies continued to pour out of Singapore warehouses, boosting 
speculation Japanese manufacturing demand is on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures have been in the doldrums for months as increased  
world supply is met with weak demand from the important Asian 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumption from Japan in manufacturing electronics and building  
offices is seen as key to reviving the moribund metal's outlook in 
that region. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts noted, however, warehouse inventories are likely to  
begin increasing in coming days as new supplies arrive from Chile, 
the world's top producer. Still, copper consumers were taking the 
opportunity to snap up supplies amid fears the rally would continue 
for days. 
</P>
<P>
	May high-grade copper rose 2.75 cents to 64.50 cents a pound.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
