<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Mom, Son Settle Lottery Feud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) -- A man who refused to share a $2.15  
million lottery award with his mother made a ``business decision'' 
to settle a lawsuit Monday and give up nearly a quarter of the 
prize. 
</P>
<P>
	Phyllis and Michael Klingebiel embraced after their lawyers  
worked out an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Klingebiel, who stopped speaking to her son after suing him  
in 1997, wants ``the chance to mend fences with her son and 
daughter-in-law,'' said her lawyer, Gary Blaustein. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Klingebiel said she and her son had a decade-old agreement  
to buy lottery tickets together and share any prizes. Each month, 
she sent him $20, while he also put in $20, to buy 40 lottery 
tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	When a ticket Klingebiel bought won the Pick-6 drawing on Oct.  
2, 1997, he called his mother and said, ``We won.'' But Klingebiel 
said he was talking about his wife, Jillanne. He said he did not 
have to share it with his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Klingebiel sued the couple in December 1997, seeking half  
the winnings. The settlement, reached on the day the trial was to 
begin, gives Mrs. Klingebiel 22.5 percent of the winnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Klingebiel's attorney, Henry Rzemieniewski, said he was  
concerned that a jury might be sympathetic to a mother in the case 
and didn't want to risk losing a greater percentage of the award. 
</P>
<P>
	``He made a business decision,'' Rzemieniewski said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
