<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 15:43:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Avoiding Education Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ducking a fight with President Clinton,  
Republican congressional leaders intend to jettison a provision the 
Senate added to education legislation recently after a pitched 
battle with Democrats, according to GOP officials. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott discussed the issue at a meeting last week, the officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have been eager to present a less confrontational  
face to the country, given their unexpected loss of House seats 
last November and the politically charged impeachment drama that 
followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Several aides, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the  
House GOP leadership in particular is eager to have Clinton's 
signature on the so-called ``ed flex'' measure as a symbol of 
Congress' ability to record achievements. 
</P>
<P>
	The underlying legislation, which has broad bipartisan support  
as well as backing of the nation's governors, would loosen strings 
on federal school aid. 
</P>
<P>
	When the measure came up on the Senate floor, Democrats sought  
to attach a variety of poll-tested proposals, including one to hire 
additional teachers toward Clinton's goal of 100,000, and another 
for after-school programs. After a standoff that lasted several 
days, Republicans voted down the major Democratic proposals. They 
then muscled through a provision of their own to allow the states 
to take $1.2 billion already approved for teacher hiring and apply 
it to educational programs for the disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-passed version of the measure contains no comparable  
provision. Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., who shepherded the bill to 
passage, said he hoped the Senate would relent. ``I hope they'll 
drop all their amendments,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has made clear his dislike for the provision, saying it  
amounted to the GOP backing out of an agreement last year to start 
hiring new teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Senate used this bill to undermine one of our most  
important educational achievements,'' Clinton said in a written 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
senators are prepared to circulate a letter that would make clear 
any veto of the bill would be upheld. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate negotiators have not yet met on the bill. They  
may not until after lawmakers return from their recess early next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their retreat, Republicans say the special education  
issue is a political winner for them and intend to bring it up 
again later in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 

</P>
<P>
	Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich has accepted appointment as a  
senior fellow at the American Enterprise Institute, a Washington 
think tank. The former Georgia lawmaker will conduct research and 
write about domestic and security policy, according to an 
announcement, which added that his initial project will be on 
health and health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich, who stepped down late last year after the Republicans  
unexpectedly lost seats in the 1998 elections, has been making paid 
speeches around the country. His political action committee is 
scheduled to hold a $1,000-per-person fund-raiser on April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich represented Atlanta's northern suburbs in Congress for  
20 years. He has been mentioned as a potential contender for 
Georgia's governor in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 

</P>
<P>
	The winnowing has begun in Florida, where Republican Sen. Connie  
Mack's decision to retire sparked a rush by House members to 
explore a possible race to succeed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Mark Foley has become the first lawmaker to take himself  
out of the race and will run instead for re-election to a fourth 
term from his district along the Atlantic coast. Foley recently was 
given a coveted spot on the House Ways and Means Committee, with 
jurisdiction over taxes, trade and other issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley's decision is good news for the GOP leadership, which is  
worried about being able to hold control of the House next year. 
``They all were very anxious for me to stay,'' Foley said of the 
leaders who talked with him, including Majority Leader Dick Armey 
and the whip, Rep. Tom DeLay, both from Texas; and Rep. Tom Davis 
of Virginia, who chairs the GOP campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley has held his seat easily since winning it in 1994, but  
President Clinton carried the district both times he ran. ``It 
would be very competitive'' if it were an open race, Foley said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Party's new chairman, Joe Andrew, is getting help  
to restructure the Democratic National Committee. Yolanda Caraway, 
a Washington consultant, will head his transition efforts, 
according to an official familiar with Andrew's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Caraway helped Ron Brown makes his transition to the DNC in  
1981. Andrew was named chairman Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said one of  
the first things Andrew plans to do is replace executive director 
Janet Green with Rob Engel, who has held a similar post with the 
House campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, whose tenure included the surprisingly successful 1998  
elections, is moving on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 05:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Oscar Parties Rage Into Wee Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- After a long Oscars ceremony, they  
partied like it's 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Winners, losers, also-rans. Famous, infamous, unknowns. They  
vamped, got kissy-faced and celebrated at post-Oscar parties raging 
into the wee hours today. 
</P>
<P>
	After the official academy Governors Ball at the downtown Los  
Angeles Music Center, limousines fanned out across Southern 
California. Many headed to West Hollywood, the most popular 
destination with six major bashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Best-director Steven Spielberg his ``Saving Private Ryan'' star  
Tom Hanks showed up at the DreamWorks-Paramount party at Barnaby's, 
where guests dined on raw oysters, shiitake mushroom pizza and 
chicken pot pie. 
</P>
<P>
	Handshaking. Hugs. Air kisses. Make that big wet kisses from  
Italy's ``Life is Beautiful'' Oscar-winner Roberto Benigni. 
</P>
<P>
	There was head-shaking, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Monica Lewinsky, shrouded in a black gown, showed up at Morton's  
for the annual Vanity Fair fest. She mugged for cameras before 
disappearing inside the fern-laden Melrose Avenue eatery. 
</P>
<P>
	The former White House intern was still inside when Jay Leno,  
king of the Lewinsky jokesters, strolled past the giant Oscar 
topiary at the Morton's entrance and went inside. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't known if Leno encountered Ms. Lewinsky, but actress  
Uma Thurman could be seen talking to her at one point. 
</P>
<P>
	It was an eclectic crowd: Madonna dancing with Ricky Martin,  
Edward Burns of ``Saving Private Ryan'' arm-in-arm with actress 
Heather Graham and ``Sling Blade'' star Dwight Yoakam with actress 
Bridget Fonda. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Hopkins, Jim Carrey, Ben Affleck, Matt Damon, Steve  
Martin, Tim Allen, Willem Dafoe, Mariah Carey were all there. 
Steven Baldwin -- blond hair slicked-back, wearing black leather 
pants and an ankle-length overcoat -- also showed up. So did Ed 
McMahon. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only party we're going to go to. We're not into  
this kind of stuff that much,'' McMahon said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Pagani, Elton John was holding court in a purple Versace  
suit. His annual AIDS bash raises more than $300,000 and partygoers 
included Janet Jackson, Rod Stewart and Leann Rimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Just up the street on Sunset Boulevard, the online Hollywood  
Stock Exchange and Excite! gathering dubbed Rock the Oscars 
featured a performance by Beck on the House of Blues stage. The 
computer-equipped party, described as a ``convergence of the 
digital world and Hollywood,'' allowed Internet users to contact 
partygoers online. 
</P>
<P>
	The pink and posh Beverly Hills Hotel hosted the Night of 100  
Stars party to raise money for Martin Scorsese's film preservation 
foundation. Ernest Borgnine, Elliot Gould, Tony Curtis and Rod 
Steiger were among those invited. 
</P>
<P>
	When the curtain came down on the 71st annual Academy Awards, a  
fleet of stretch limousines were idling outside. But departures 
were delayed for the obligatory rounds at the Governors Ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Call it networking: Lots of let's-do-lunch and  
have-your-people-call-my-people banter. Governors Ball guests were 
greeted by the sounds of a string band, appropriate considering the 
age of the majority of the guests. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those inside was 89-year-old director Elia Kazan, whose  
lifetime achievement award created a stir in Hollywood. Sitting at 
a table with Karl Malden, Kazan said: ``I'm glad it's over, but it 
was a nice evening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among Oscar winners making the rounds of the ball were Benigni,  
James Coburn, Judi Dench and Gwyneth Paltrow. But most of the stars 
were boarding limos an hour later to hit other parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 05:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
