<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 16:12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UConn's Freeman Making a Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- Postseason play has been payback time for  
Connecticut's Kevin Freeman. 
</P>
<P>
	Snubbed when it came time to pick the Big East's first, second  
or third all-conference teams, the power forward's rebounding and 
clutch shooting have helped carry the Huskies (32-2) to their first 
Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman had 13 points and a career-high 15 rebounds -- 10 off the  
offensive boards -- in UConn's 67-62 win against Gonzaga to advance 
to St. Petersburg, Fla. In the final minutes, he hit two free 
throws to give UConn the lead for good at 57-55 and then iced the 
game with two more from the line with 6.2 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	With the game on the line, there were no butterflies. Just net.  
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully I can have that same confidence and God will bless  
me with the same strokes to allow the ball to go in,'' Freeman said 
Monday. ``It's just a matter of focus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies, winners of the West Regional, take on Ohio State on  
Saturday. The Buckeyes (27-8) advanced to the Final Four with a 
77-74 South Regional final win against St. John's. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks after the conference snub, the accolades are  
mounting. Freeman was named to the West Regional All-Tournament 
team. And his performance in the conference tournament earlier this 
month earned him Most Outstanding Player honors. 
</P>
<P>
	His award-winning efforts aren't anything out of the ordinary  
for the 6-foot-7 junior, say his teammates and coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has the incredible ability to will himself to do things,''  
said coach Jim Calhoun. ``He's done it in a humble sort of way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calhoun said he marveled at Freeman's 10 offensive boards  
against the Bulldogs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was absolutely phenomenal,'' Calhoun said. ``Coaches just  
don't marvel when you've had the great fortune to have some great 
players play for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team's leading rebounder, the muscular Freeman is averaging  
7.3 boards a game. With 12.6 points a game, he's the third top 
scorer behind the higher profile tandem of All-American Richard 
Hamilton and flashy point guard Khalid El-Amin. 
</P>
<P>
	When they've gone cold at times -- El-Amin was 0-for-12 against  
Gonzaga -- the Huskies look inside to Freemen and get results. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kevin brings toughness. He brings it consistently,'' said  
center Jake Voskuhl. ``He's playing the best basketball right now 
that he's played since he's been here. The sky's the limit for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman and the 6-11 Voskuhl have played together for three  
years, and with the addition of 6-8 sophomore Edmund Saunders, are 
formidable in the post. The three combine for nearly 19 boards a 
game and can read each other like a road map. 
</P>
<P>
	They decided early on in the second half of the Gonzaga game to  
get every rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just looked at Kevin, Kevin looked at me,'' said Voskuhl.  
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies went on to get 10 second-chance points in the last  
eight minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the communication, especially with me and Jake down  
low, is something that develops over time. We have a natural 
bond,'' said Freeman. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman said he's put the Big East snub behind him and just  
tries to prove every game he's one of the top players in the 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people don't want to recognize it they won't,'' he said.  
``Hopefully we'll continue to win and I'll continue to be the X 
factor that beats you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 21:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Royal Pleads Guilty on Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd. pleaded guilty  
Monday to falsifying oil discharge records on a ship that was 
stopped in the Los Angeles port. 
</P>
<P>
	The cruise line admitted that its employees presented false  
pollution prevention records to U.S. Coast Guard officers during 
routine inspections on the ship Nordic Prince, according to the 
U.S. attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea relates to three separate incidents between January and  
October 1994, when the ship was berthed in the Port of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The crew members presented records that claimed the oils and  
oil-contaminated waters had been properly treated prior to being 
thrown overboard. But the equipment designed to separate oil from 
wastewater was inoperative. 
</P>
<P>
	The log and records are required under the Clean Water Act.  
</P>
<P>
	``We did these things and they were terrible. There's no excuse.  
It is a very different company (now) environmentally,'' said Royal 
Caribbean spokeswoman Lynn Martenstein from Miami, where the 
company is headquartered. 
</P>
<P>
	The company faces up to $1.5 million in fines. Each of the three  
counts carries a maximum penalty of a $500,000 fine. Sentencing is 
set for June 28. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Martenstein, the company also pleaded guilty to the  
same charges in June 1998 in federal courts in Miami and San Juan, 
Puerto Rico. In those cases, Royal Caribbean was ordered to pay $9 
million in fines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nordic Prince was sold in 1995.  



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:06:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Six Skaters Make 4-Revolution Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) - There were quads in the air and on the  
ice and it was just the qualifying rounds at the World Figure 
Skating Championships today. 
</P>
<P>
	Six skaters completed the four-revolution jump, the most ever in  
a competition and American Tim Goebel became the first skater to 
land a quad salchow in the world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond the jumps, the real jockeying for positions began today  
the Russians leading the way as expected. Yevgeny Plushenko won one 
group and defending world champion Alexei Yagudin won the other, 
despite a sore left leg. 
</P>
<P>
	American champion Michael Weiss came in second to Plushenko and  
former Olympic champion Alexei Urmanov was second to Yagudin. 
</P>
<P>
	Later today the pairs have their short programs. Russians Yelena  
Berezhnaya and Anton Sikarulidze are the defending world champions 
and hope to rebound from recent poor performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday, in the men's qualifying, the quads came in quantity and  
quality, 
</P>
<P>
	Plushenko, Elvis Stojko, Weiss, Goebel, Guo Zhengxin of China  
and Anthony Liu of Australia hit them, marking the most in a single 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, three different skaters did them at the 1997 Grand  
Prix final -- future Olympic champion Ilya Kulik, Urmanov and Stojko 
hit them. Stojko and two others hit them at the 1997 world 
championships finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss finally nailed a clean quad toe loop. In 1997 he thought  
he had one but the videotape replay hours later showed he had 
slightly two-footed it. There was no doubt about it Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I initially wasn't planning on trying it but as soon as I saw  
two of them hit theirs out there, I knew if I wanted to be up there 
in first or second I had to go for it, '' he said. ``It worked 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss also did triple-triple combinations and three other triple  
jumps, but fell on his second triple axel attempt. Still that put 
him ahead of Stojko, pushing the three-time world champion to third 
in the qualifying group 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko hit his first quad but fell on his second. ``I think I  
was just a little sloppy on the landing,'' Stojko said of his brush 
with the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	He found the qualifications, which count in the scoring this  
year, difficult to adjust to. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very hard to do at this point -- to give everything or  
hold back,'' said Stojko, who turned 27 Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He also didn't do any triple-triple combinations.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew the triple-triples would make the difference,'' said  
Weiss, who had marks between 5.6 and 5.8 but, more importantly, the 
advantage over Stojko with five of the second judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Plushenko started strong, with his quad but had slight errors on  
a number of his other jumps. Nonetheless, he ranked ahead of Weiss 
on all but the Swiss judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Yagudin, who has been consistent throughout the season and  
delivered an awesome quad and quad-triple in practice the day 
before, won his group easily without even attempting one. 
</P>
<P>
	His marks were nearly all 5.8s and 5.9s.  
</P>
<P>
	He did eight triples in doing just enough to get into first  
without putting additional pressure on a sore left calf muscle that 
caused him to shake his leg as soon as he finished. 
</P>
<P>
	Goebel came in fifth helped by his quad salchow. In contrast to  
the toe loops, which the other skaters did, the salchow does not 
have use the skate's toe pick to help pole-vault the skater up. 
</P>
<P>
	Goebel started slowly, putting two hands down on a triple axel.  
Then he got up and landed the quad salchow, which he had done 
previously at the Goodwill Games and junior Grand Prix finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The qualifying round advances 15 skaters from each group and  
counts for 20 percent of the total score. 
</P>
<P>
	The short program accounts for an additional 30 with Thursday's  
long program counting the remaining 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
