<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 15:36:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Iraq Executes 93 Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Iraq has executed 93 political detainees in  
a prison near Baghdad, a human rights group affiliated with an 
Iraqi opposition party reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The London-based Center for Human Rights said the executions  
took place in November in Radwaniya prison, just west of Baghdad. 
</P>
<P>
	The group provided a list identifying those it said were  
executed, all of whom it said had been detained since an abortive 
Shiite Muslim uprising in southern Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	The Center for Human Rights, which is linked to the Iraqi  
Communist Party, said it got its information from sources inside 
Iraq whom it did not identify. It said 63 prisoners were executed 
in Nov. 6 and 30 were executed Nov. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bodies of the executed prisoners were not returned to  
their families and instead they were buried in mass graves in the 
nearby Mashtal area,'' the group said in a statement faxed to The 
Associated Press in Cairo. 
</P>
<P>
	President Saddam Hussein's government refuses to comment on such  
charges, and there is no way to get independent confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraqi opposition groups have accused Iraq of systematically  
executing political prisoners. In January, they claimed 81 
political prisoners were executed in Abu Ghraib prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The Center for Human Rights claims thousands are imprisoned at  
Radwaniya, some of them Kurds who have been detained since the 
start of the 1980-88 Iraq-Iran war. 
</P>
<P>
	The group called on U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, all U.N.  
human rights organizations, the Arab League, the Organization of 
the Islamic Conference and the Red Cross to send teams to inspect 
Iraqi prisons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
