<DOCNO> APW19990322.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 17:13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Shares Personal Side With Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, in crisp white  
shirt and tie, paused a beat before he decided to share a secret 
with some giggling first-graders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did have a treehouse,'' said Gore. ``I had a really neat  
treehouse when I was growing up on the farm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a few minutes as he opened yet another campaign day, Gore  
the candidate turned into Gore the teacher, Gore the student, even 
Gore the grieving son. At least for a bit, he moved from dry policy 
and reveled in the attention he got from youngsters and their 
teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	He beamed as he walked into a gymnasium at a Sioux Falls  
elementary school filled with squealing youngsters. ``I need 
somebody to give me a high five,'' said Gore, as he plunged into a 
crowd of toddlers. 
</P>
<P>
	He went down on one knee to ask a youngster, ``What's the most  
important thing about reading?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He later adjourned to the school library, where he sat before  
about a dozen first-graders, reading from the story ``The Giving 
Tree.'' Again dropping to a knee, Gore unbuttoned his suit coat as 
he chatted with the youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	``How old are you?'' asked one.  
</P>
<P>
	``Why I'm about to have my birthday, I'm 50,'' said Gore, to  
groans from the youngsters. ``Does that sound old to you?'' asked 
Gore, seeming surprised. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent campaign swings, Gore has tried to show a more human  
and personal side. There are clear reasons for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls have shown an overwhelming majority of voters know who  
Gore is, but many have questions about his leadership abilities and 
his ability to move out of President Clinton's shadow. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the process of introducing ourself to America,'' said  
aide Chris Lehane. ``Who he is and what he's all about. It's quite 
a story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's latest campaign trip has included some old-fashioned  
political business as well. Gore was in the state to collect the 
endorsements of Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle and South Dakota 
Sen. Tim Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not every day the vice president gets a two-fer,'' said  
Daschle. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign played the song ``Wild Thing'' over the public  
address system as backers waited for the speeches. 
</P>
<P>
	On a quieter personal note, Gore noted that Daschle and he  
shared family pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just recently, both Tom and I lost our dads,'' he said, moving  
on to tell a poignant story about Daschle's father. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said in an interview that he finds it tough to talk about  
himself and break through the legendary stiffness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not used to it because the way I was raised you don't talk  
about yourself too much,'' said Gore. ``But in a campaign, you've 
got to introduce yourself and the experiences which have shaped 
your life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were clear limits to the down-home campaign informality on  
Monday. Gore and his entourage blew into the elementary school with 
a retinue that ground normal activities to a halt. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore planned a roundtable with about 20 teachers, saying that he  
wanted to listen to their concerns, that ``one of the best things 
we could do is have a conversation about what works and what 
doesn't work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He sat sipping tea, from a cup sporting a teacher's apple, and  
responded to teachers' pointed questions about class size, pay and 
preparation time. The conversation was animated, but more in the 
form of a presentation than a conversation. Gore aides pressed him 
to move on. ``They're sending me increasingly agitated notes,'' 
Gore said as aides repeatedly handed him slips of paper. 
</P>
<P>
	Most teachers were keeping one eye on the security guards posted  
at each door, and the staff photographer prowling the room. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the best class I've ever had,'' said Gore, as he  
shuffled off to the next event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Don't Expect Benigni in Mainstream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- You can hear the movie pitch now. ``Life is  
Beautiful'' meets ``48 Hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Benigni is the wacky Italian policeman who comes to LA  
to solve an international crime and gets teamed with a smart-mouth 
from the 'hood. 
</P>
<P>
	Only it's probably not going to happen any time soon.  
</P>
<P>
	With his triumph at the Oscars on Sunday night and joyful  
victory dance across the seats, Benigni becomes one of the hottest 
-- if most unlikely -- new properties in Hollywood: a small, balding, 
Italian comic who speaks heavily accented English. 
</P>
<P>
	But for all the offers that are likely to come his way, for all  
those buddy movies and fish-out-of-water high-concept tales, don't 
look for this exuberant actor-writer-director to plunge into the 
American movie mainstream. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's going to be Benigni for hire,'' said Harvey  
Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax Films, which released Benigni's 
triple Oscar-winning ``Life is Beautiful.'' ``He's his own writer. 
He's his own director. He doesn't have to sell his services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Backstage at the Academy Awards, Benigni confirmed as much. He  
said that while the Oscars, including his surprising best actor 
honor, have obviously changed his life, he plans to follow what he 
called ``my same style'' and make the ``same little movies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Because when you remain little,'' he explained, ``you can  
watch (the) magnificence of the creation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A big star in his native country, Benigni has enjoyed creative  
control for years, drawing on his experiences working as an actor 
with some of the greatest international directors, including 
Constantin Costa-Gavras and Federico Fellini. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Benigni had not gained the sort of American recognition  
found by such Italian actors as Marcello Mastroianni or Sophia 
Loren -- until ``Life is Beautiful,'' the tragicomic story of an 
Italian Jew who uses humor to shield his young son from the horrors 
of a World War II concentration camp. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Oscars, Benigni electrified the ceremony with his  
unabashed expressions of joy and gratitude, pulling off a 
surprising first: winning as best actor in a foreign film for 
``Life is Beautiful,'' which he also wrote and directed. The only 
other performer in a foreign-language film to get an acting Oscar 
was Miss Loren, for ``Two Women'' in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Benigni became the first filmmaker in 50 years to  
direct his own Oscar-winning performance. In 1948, Laurence Olivier 
directed and starred in ``Hamlet,'' for which he won the best 
acting prize. 
</P>
<P>
	The honors for ``Life is Beautiful'' awards capped a big night  
for Miramax, whose ``Shakespeare in Love'' led the evening with 
seven awards, including best picture, best actress for Gwyneth 
Paltrow and best original screenplay for Marc Norman and Tom 
Stoppard. DreamWorks' ``Saving Private Ryan'' won five Oscars, 
including best director for Steven Spielberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Lions Gate, which had its own Oscar success with awards for  
James Coburn's supporting role in ``Affliction'' and Bill Condon's 
script for ``Gods and Monsters,'' is planning to re-release 
Benigni's 1994 comedy ``The Monster,'' about a bumbling man 
mistaken by police as a serial killer. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can do anything he wants right now,'' said Lions Gate  
president Mark Urman. ``But he's not just a talent for hire. He is 
somebody who will create films around his persona.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 16:43:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Some 15,000 families have seized 5,000  
acres of vacant land in one of Venezuela's largest squatter 
invasions, Infrastructure Minister Luis Reyes said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A nationwide wave of invasions began after Hugo Chavez, the  
leader of a failed 1992 coup attempt who champions the rights of 
the poor, was sworn in as president Feb. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez has refused to call in the National Guard to evict the  
squatters, provoking a storm of protest from state governors and 
businessmen who said he was condoning the invasions and scaring off 
foreign investors worried about respect for private property. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez said he wants the issue settled peacefully and is hoping  
to persuade the squatters to leave by implementing a land reform 
and housing program. 
</P>
<P>
	Well over half of Venezuela's 23 million people live in poverty,  
and the housing deficit is estimated at more than 1 million homes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- Salvadoran police confirmed  
Monday that a Cuban exile suspected of paying two men to carry out 
bombings in Havana entered the country using false credentials. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban authorities last week showed a video of Luis Posada  
Carriles walking on the streets of San Salvador. The video was 
presented during the trial of Ernesto Cruz Leon, one of two 
Salvadorans accused of planting bombs in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors claim Posada Carriles hired the Salvadorans to carry  
out the attacks in an attempt to hurt tourism on the island. An 
Italian tourist died in one bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Salvadoran President Armando Calderon Sol last week ordered an  
investigation into the movements of Cruz Leon and condemned what he 
called Cuban ``espionage'' in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban authorities are seeking the death penalty for Cruz Leon  
and the other suspect, Otto Rodriguez Llerena. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The government is trying to negotiate a  
solution to the case of an Israeli-born media mogul who lost his 
TV-station and citizenship after airing reports critical of the 
military, newspapers reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Baruch Ivcher, majority owner of Channel 2, is meeting with  
Peruvian officials in Washington to find a solution to the problem 
that has come to symbolize allegations that President Alberto 
Fujimori is trying to silence media criticism of himself and the 
armed forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru's Interior Ministry revoked Ivcher's Peruvian citizenship  
in 1997, after Channel 2 broadcast reports linking the military to 
cases of torture, corruption and telephone espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry said Ivcher had never renounced his Israeli  
citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Peruvian law prohibits foreigners from owning television  
or radio stations, a court stripped Ivcher of control of Channel 2. 
It awarded control to the pro-government minority owners. Fujimori 
controls Peru's judicial system, human rights groups charge. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The nephew of a former Mexican president  
registered Monday to run for the presidency of the ruling party, 
which for the first time in its 70 years in power will choose its 
leadership through an internal election. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodolfo Echeverria Ruiz, 53, will face former Labor Secretary  
Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez in a secret ballot by the party's 
governing council on March 30. He is the nephew of former President 
Luis Echeverria, who governed from 1970 to 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	No other candidates registered for the party presidency.  
</P>
<P>
	Echeverria Ruiz, a former state legislator and ambassador to  
Cuba, is backed by the party's old-style politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez Fernandez is widely seen as enjoying the support of  
President Ernesto Zedillo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI,  
previously allowed the sitting president to choose the party 
leadership and last week's announcement of an open election took 
many by surprise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
