<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally higher  
Monday, with the key index in Hong Kong rising for the second 
consecutive session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 24.32 points, or 0.2 percent, closing at 
11,107.24. On Friday, the index had surged 423.60 points, or 4 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnover fell to 4.90 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. $628  
million), down from Friday's 6.79 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. 
$870 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said the Hang Seng Index rose on continued selective  
buying of blue-chip stocks following Friday's sharp rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was relatively quiet because of a market holiday in  
Japan on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, Hong Kong investors have been using the Tokyo's Nikkei  
Stock Average as a major trading indicator. The Hong Kong market 
rose sharply on Friday in reaction to strong gains in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Singapore closed mostly higher, driven by gains  
in property and finance stocks. The Straits Times Index closed 
24.69 points, or 1.7 percent, to 1,497.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan share prices also closed higher, with the key index  
breaching the psychologically important 7,000-point mark following 
a late rally in chip stocks and encouraging trade data. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's Weighted Stock Price Index rose 49.85  
points, or 0.7 percent, to 7,043.23. The index hasn't settled above 
7,000 points since Dec. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors continued to accumulate shares in semiconductor  
companies Monday as the industry shows signs of recovery, dealers 
said. The gains in the market were also helped by news during the 
session showing Taiwan's economy may be on the rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan's Ministry of Economic Affairs reported Monday that  
export orders for the first two months of this year rose 2.12 
percent from a year ago, to U.S. $18.47 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower, with brokers  
saying the local market was quiet due to a lack of any real 
direction. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 8.50 points, or 
0.3 percent, to 2,144.45. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher. The 30-company  
Philippine Stock Exchange Index (PSE Index) rose 12.03 points, or 
0.6 percent, to 2,018.49. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed slightly higher. The All  
Ordinaries Index rose 1.00 point to 2,985.5. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean share prices closed higher. The Korea  
Composite Stock Price rose 3.52 points, or 0.5 percent, to 607.74. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower in thin  
trading, with investors expecting more bad news from companies 
announcing their earnings within the next few weeks. The Composite 
Index fell 6.3 points, or 1.2 percent, to 507.55. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower on profit-taking. The  
Composite Index fell 1.934 points, or 0.49 percent, to 392.283. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices ended slightly lower in thin trading.  
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index fell 1.60 points, or 0.4 
percent, to 366.09. 
</P>
</TEXT>
