<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *MediaOne Group Inc. rose 7 3/4 to 68 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
 *Comcast Corp. Class A special common stock fell 6 1/2 to 66 3/8 in Nasdaq 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast is buying MediaOne for $48.65 billion in stock,  
combining the nation's third- and fourth-largest cable television 
providers. 

</P>
<P>
 *CHS Electronics fell 2 1/16 to 3 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Miami-based distributor of computer products restated 1998  
results. The company said a senior executive in Europe overstated 
vendor rebates during the last nine months of 1998, which in turn 
inflated profits. The executive, identified as Pasquale Giordano, 
resigned Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced a cost-cutting program that includes  
the elimination of as many as 600 jobs, or 10 percent of the 
company's work force. The company earned 23 cents a share in the 
fourth quarter of 1998, not the 47 cents it had earlier reported. 

</P>
<P>
 *U.S. Filter Corp. fell 1/8 to 30 3/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Vivendi, one of France's largest industrial conglomerates, said  
it would buy U.S. Filter in a $6.2 billion, two-step cash deal, 
giving the French company a foothold in the U.S. water-treatment 
business. 

</P>
<P>
 *Jenny Craig Inc. rose 1 1/16 to 4 1/2.    	
</P>
<P>
	Jenny Craig the diet and vitamin company will begin selling a  
line of vitamins, minerals and dietary supplements through its new 
Web site. 

</P>
<P>
 *Gucci Group NV rose 2 1/8 to 83 1/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	A Dutch Court ruled Monday that Gucci, the Amsterdam-based  
fashion group, must begin negotiations with French luxury-goods 
maker LVMH Moet Hennessey Louis Vuitton over LVMH's $7.86 billion 
offer for Gucci. The court restored LVMH's voting rights on its 26 
percent stake in Gucci, which had been suspended March 3. The court 
also upheld Friday's agreement between French retailer 
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute and Gucci, which provides that PPR will 
take a 40-percent interest in Gucci. However, the court suspended 
any parts of the agreement which would hamper the negotiations 
between Gucci and LVMH. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Dell Computer fell 2 3/8 to 37 7/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities trimmed its revenue and  
earnings estimates for the company, saying personal computer sales 
growth will likely be lower in 1999 than in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
 *Broadcast.com rose 31 1/2 to 116 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
 *Yahoo! fell 5 to 165. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcast.com shares rose on rumors that Yahoo! was about to  
acquire the Internet audio and video provider. Dallas-based 
Broadcast.com is perhaps best known for its Webcast of Victoria's 
Secret live fashion show last month. 

</P>
<P>
 *Finet Holdings Corp. rose 1 1/2 to 4 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company named Gary A. Palmer chief financial officer. Palmer  
has been acting CFO since December. Finet provides e-commerce home 
financing services. 

</P>
<P>
 *DoubleClick fell 2 3/4 to 177.    	
</P>
<P>
	The stock backed off after trading as high as 200. The Internet  
advertising company formed a partnership with Comcast Online 
Communications in which Comcast, the Internet access company, will 
use DoubleClick technology to target ads to Internet users and 
provide detailed advertising reports. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
