<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Group Targets Bush, Dole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An abortion rights group launched a series of  
television ads today that accuse presidential hopefuls George W. 
Bush and Elizabeth Dole of camouflaging strict anti-abortion 
positions. 
</P>
<P>
	The two early favorites for the Republican presidential  
nomination, who have also been attacked by anti-abortion groups 
questioning their commitment to the cause, are now the target of 
ads bought by the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action 
League 
</P>
<P>
	The ads, which began airing Monday morning on stations in  
Manchester, N.H., and Des Moines, Iowa, use quotes from the pair in 
an attempt to show they are opposed to abortion. The ads accuse 
them of trying to ``hide their extreme views,'' said NARAL director 
Kate Michelman. 
</P>
<P>
	``George W. Bush opposes a woman's right to choose. Elizabeth  
Dole opposes a women's right to choose,'' she said. ``But they both 
know they must communicate more moderate views in order to be 
elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michelman would not say how much money was being spent on the  
campaign or how often the ads would run. ``It is a significant 
buy,'' she said. The ads are running around morning and evening 
newscasts in the two cities, and later will be broadcast in other 
regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the governor of Texas, has said he is opposed to abortion,  
with exceptions only for the life of the mother, rape and incest. 
Though he personally would like abortions to be outlawed, he says, 
Americans' ``hearts are not right'' on the issue, so Republicans 
should fight for incremental steps such as banning late-term 
abortions and requiring parental consent for abortions for 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't expect to get everybody's vote should I decide to run  
for the presidency,'' Bush said Monday. ``I'm pro-life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, a former president of the American Red Cross, has  
declined to discuss her abortion views in any depth since entering 
the presidential fray, but her spokesman, Ari Fleischer, said she 
is ``pro-life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These ads illustrate what's wrong with politics today,''  
Fleischer said. ``Eleven months before the primaries, special 
interest groups are running negative attack ads.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa is the site of the first presidential caucuses in 2000. New  
Hampshire holds the first primary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 07:23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Retailer Moves Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIBERTY LAKE, Wash. (AP) -- Online computer-equipment retailer  
Egghead.com is moving its headquarters across the state to 
Vancouver, as the company transforms itself into an Internet-only 
retailer. 
</P>
<P>
	Egghead decided last summer to consolidate operations in  
Vancouver, but indicated at the time that headquarters would remain 
in Liberty Lake, where it has been since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the 25 remaining Egghead workers in Liberty Lake were  
told that the headquarters -- and their jobs -- will be relocated to 
Vancouver by June. 
</P>
<P>
	The employees, all in the finance department, will receive  
layoff notices, and Egghead will discuss possible transfers to 
Vancouver, the company said. Employees unable to move will receive 
severance pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the more than 200 employees in Vancouver have been  
transferred from Liberty Lake, Portland, Ore., and Hood River, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The consolidation followed Egghead's $36 million acquisition of  
Surplus Direct, a Hood River company that sold close-out computer 
hardware through catalogs and the Internet, followed by a shift to 
online-only retailing. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Egghead announced that it was closing its remaining  
80 stores, renaming itself Egghead.com and shifting its focus to 
selling both hardware and software on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	When the move was announced, Egghead employed about 1,000  
people, most of whom have since been laid off. 
</P>
<P>
	Egghead was founded in 1984 in Issaquah, a suburb east of  
Seattle, and operated a growing chain of software-only retail 
stores. The chain eventually grew to more than 200 stores in 30 
states and had about 2,500 employees. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0052 </DOCNO>
