<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 23:22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Warns Yugoslav President  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fearful that a half-dozen countries,  
especially Albania and Macedonia, could be drawn into a conflict 
with Yugoslavia, the Clinton administration is warning President 
Slobodan Milosevic not to lash out beyond Kosovo in the event of a 
NATO attack. There would be ``grave consequences'' if Milosevic 
sent troops beyond Serbia's borders, the State Department cautioned 
Monday. With NATO gearing up to bomb Serb targets for blocking a 
political settlement in Kosovo and violating a cease-fire 
agreement, the potential for a spillover troubles U.S. 
policy-makers. Their aim is to confine the conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB Crash Investigation Nears End  
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- Despite the longest investigation of its  
31-year history, the National Transportation Safety Board remains 
uncertain about what precisely caused USAir Flight 427 to go 
spiraling into a ravine outside Pittsburgh in 1994. Instead, after 
a hearing beginning Tuesday, the board members are expected to 
conclude that there are lingering problems with the type of plane 
that crashed -- the Boeing 737, the world's most common jetliner -- 
and that its manufacturer and the Federal Aviation Administration 
should work to fix them, according to source close to the board. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Caffeine May Be Good for You  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Caffeine is not addictive for most people, a  
new study concludes, and has little effect on human health. 
According to a much-promoted French study released Monday during 
the American Chemical Society's annual meeting, drinking up to 
three cups of coffee a day has no effect on the part of the brain 
responsible for addiction. And it may actually be good for you. If 
you're a rat. After spending two years with 30 rodents, researcher 
Astrid Nehlig of the French National Health Medical Research 
Institute found that moderate consumption increases energy and 
renders addiction ``quite unlikely.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat Meets with U.S. Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat arrived in  
Washington on Monday night to build support for eventual 
Palestinian independence, amid growing pressures for him to 
postpone a May 4 declaration of statehood. Arafat spent nearly an 
hour and a half meeting with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
at her Georgetown home. Afterward, Albright said President Clinton 
and Arafat would discuss Palestinian concerns over the legal 
questions surrounding the May 4 date. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Malaysian Official's Trial Ends  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- The closely watched trial of  
ousted Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim ended abruptly Tuesday 
when defense lawyers refused to make their closing arguments. A 
verdict in the sensational sex and corruption trial was expected 
early next month. Anwar who was sacked and arrested last September, 
has repeatedly said that all 10 charges against him were fabricated 
by his political enemies who worked with the police to end the 
challenge he posed to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. 

</P>
<P>
	Avalanche: Four Dead, Six Missing  
</P>
<P>
	TURNAGAIN PASS, Alaska (AP) -- Volunteers recovered two more  
bodies Monday from an avalanche that swept through a popular 
snowmobiling spot the day before, raising the death toll to four. 
As many as six other people were missing. The 30-foot wave of 
powdery snow roared down the mountainside Sunday afternoon, while 
hundreds of snowmobilers enjoyed temperatures in the 40s and bright 
sunshine. 

</P>
<P>
	Report Praises Pentagon on Illness  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators credited the  
Pentagon with significant progress in handling Gulf War illness 
issues but cited flaws in its reporting of some cases. The 
government acknowledges that illnesses suffered by thousands of 
veterans are real, but years of study have not come up with clear 
diagnoses or clear evidence of causes. About 100,000 of the 700,000 
American men and women who served in the Persian Gulf in 1991 say 
they are sick. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices fell Tuesday morning on  
profit-taking in reaction to the sharp advance on Friday. The 
Nikkei shed 359.68 points to close at 16,019.10. 

</P>
<P>
	SuperSonics 92, 76ers 76  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) - Gary Payton scored 26 points and the Seattle  
SuperSonics held Allen Iverson to 14 points in a 92-76 victory over 
the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday night. The Sonics beat 
Philadelphia for the 12th straight time and ended their two-game 
losing streak. Iverson did not play the last 15 minutes because he 
got a split lower lip in the third period. Detlef Schrempf had 17 
points and 10 rebounds and Dale Ellis added 11 off the bench for 
Seattle. Larry Hughes and Matt Geiger added 13 points apiece for 
Philadelphia. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
