<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Benigni's Village Celebrates Oscars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERGAIO, Italy (AP) -- It was drizzly and chilly at 4 a.m., but  
the Tuscan village where Roberto Benigni was born was still wide 
awake when their hometown boy made good on Oscar night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roberto! Roberto! Roberto!'' the crowd watching at Vergaio's  
community center cried out when Benigni's Holocaust fable ``Life is 
Beautiful'' won the Academy Award for best foreign film. 
</P>
<P>
	Benigni, the son of a poor farmer who survived a German labor  
camp during World War II, was born 46 years ago in Vergaio, a 
village of 3,000 people about 15 miles northwest of Florence. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost everyone there stayed up at least part of the night to  
watch the Oscar broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	And they weren't disappointed. The exuberant Benigni also  
bounded off with the coveted best actor award and his movie snagged 
a third Oscar for the musical score. 
</P>
<P>
	As Vergaio's band struck up a tune, corks popped and people  
jumped to their feet, dancing, kissing and hugging each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Already one of Italy's most popular comedians, Benigni's  
Hollywood success has turned him into a national hero. The movie 
has also raised hopes of a renaissance in Italian cinema, which has 
a distinguished history but has fallen into the doldrums. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said Benigni's Oscars ``honor  
Italian cinema and culture in addition to being a great personal 
success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italy has now won a dozen Oscars for best foreign film. But only  
three have come in the last quarter-century. ``Life is Beautiful'' 
became the most successful foreign film ever in the United States, 
with a box office take of $35.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian director Bernardo Bertolucci, who won nine Oscars for  
his 1988 film ``The Last Emperor,'' said Monday that each time a 
foreign film gets a major prize, it levels the Hollywood-dominated 
playing field a little. 
</P>
<P>
	Benigni is the first Italian and the first non-English speaker  
to win the best actor award, although best actress honors went 
twice to Italians: Sophia Loren in 1961 for ``Two Women'' and Anna 
Magnani in 1955 for ``The Rose Tattoo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benigni wrote, directed and starred in the tale of an Italian  
Jewish father who uses humor to shield his son from the horrors of 
a concentration camp. He drew inspiration for his role from how his 
own father Luigi spoke of his wartime ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order not to scare me and my sisters, he tried to tell us  
the story really full of gladness, full of life. And this was 
really touching, very touching,'' Benigni said last month. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Oscar ceremony, Benigni honored victims of the  
Holocaust, which include around 7,000 Italian Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to dedicate this movie to the subject: those who  
are not here, those who gave their lives in order that we can say: 
life is beautiful,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
