<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Envoy, Serb Leader Meet  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Special U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke  
came to Belgrade today in an 11th-hour bid to persuade Yugoslavia's 
president to accept a Kosovo peace plan or face NATO attack. An 
attack could come soon after Holbrooke wraps up his talks tonight 
in the Yugoslav capital with hard-line leader Slobodan Milosevic. 
However, chances for any agreement appeared bleak. In a statement 
broadcast as the talks began, Milosevic slammed the Americans and 
their allies. ``You people should be ashamed because you are 
getting ready to use force against a small European nation because 
it protects its territory against separatism and its people against 
terrorism...'' state television quoted Milosevic as saying. 

</P>
<P>
	Fighting Intensifies in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	SRBICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanian residents of this  
Kosovo town said black-masked Yugoslav soldiers shot to death as 
many as 22 unarmed people in a weekend campaign to crush separatist 
resistance. Fighting continued in Kosovo today, and ethnic 
Albanians said at least five villages were burning in Drenica along 
with others elsewhere. Serb authorities denied the ethnic Albanian 
reports. ``Albanian terrorists and separatists are trying with 
fresh new manipulations about mass killings to provoke an 
international reaction and increase the pressure on Yugoslavia,'' 
said Col. Bozidar Filic, spokesman for Serb police in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian To Defend Himself  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian won the right to  
represent himself at his first murder trial today. After the 
ruling, 12 jurors and two alternates quickly were selected out of a 
pool of 80 people. Opening statements got under way this afternoon. 
Kevorkian is charged with the videotaped suicide of a man with Lou 
Gerhig's disease. The retired pathologist will be allowed to 
consult with lawyers David Gorosh and Lisa Dwyer during this trial, 
but he said that defending himself was ``what I've planned all 
along.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Two Dead, Six Missing in Avalanche  
</P>
<P>
	TURNAGAIN PASS, Alaska (AP) -- Volunteers with 10-foot poles  
repeatedly poked the snow today in a search for the bodies of as 
many as six people who may have been swept off their snowmobiles in 
an avalanche that killed two others. Two snowmobilers were found 
dead, and State Trooper 1st Sgt. Paul Burke said six others were 
thought to be missing, based on phone calls overnight from people 
reporting that friends or relatives hadn't returned. Troopers also 
were analyzing a videotape taken by an eyewitness to try to 
pinpoint where some victims may be buried. The video shows several 
snowmobilers trying to outrun a part of the slide. They disappear 
in smoky clouds and aren't seen again. 

</P>
<P>
	OPEC Plan Prompts Gas Price Hike  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- OPEC's plan to reduce the world's oil  
supply by about 2.6 percent has already prompted price hikes at 
gasoline pumps in the United States and elsewhere. Formal approval 
of the cuts could push gasoline prices even higher, analysts said. 
Prices shot up more than 9 percent at self-service pumps in the 
United States, where unleaded regular averaged nearly $1.03 in the 
latest survey, compared with just over 94 cents two weeks ago, 
according to the Lundberg Survey. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft To Begin Settlement Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. expects to begin negotiations  
with the government soon in an effort to settle its landmark 
antitrust case, but the sides remain far apart on core issues after 
almost five months of an acrimonious courtroom fight. The company 
indicated anew today that it would consider changing some of its 
most controversial agreements with the nation's computer makers and 
Internet providers. But the software giant won't accept 
government-demanded restrictions on what new features it can add to 
its Windows operating system software, which runs roughly 90 
percent of the world's personal computers. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Down 13.04  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell today, meandering throughout  
the session before ending off 13.04 at 9,890.51. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 1,730-1,213. Cable TV and Internet stocks 
provided some upward momentum, but personal computer shares sold 
off, leaving the Nasdaq down 25.35 at 2,395.92. 

</P>
<P>
	Moya Falters at Lipton  
</P>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Carlos Moya was on the verge of losing  
his No. 1 tennis ranking to Pete Sampras after being beaten today 
by a Frenchman ranked 74th in the world. Moya, playing his third 
three-set match in three days, lost 3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (11-9) to 
Sebastien Grosjean in the fourth round of the Lipton Championships. 
Sampras was to play Albert Costa later and needed a victory to 
reclaim No. 1. Moya became the first Spaniard to top the computer 
rankings when he overtook Sampras last week. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
