<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Finish Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and corn futures prices finished sharply  
higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid hopes the government 
would purchase more farm products for export to Russia. Wheat also 
rose. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans led the gains on speculation the U.S. Agriculture  
Department might announce it planned another donation to cash-strapped 
Russia, with soybean meal or oil as the centerpiece of that package. 
</P>
<P>
        Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said after a meeting with  
Russian officials that they had requested more food aid this year and 
that the U.S. agency would consider that request. 
</P>
<P>
        The Clinton administration is under pressure to boost exports  
as the trade deficit grows and farmers suffer from weak sales because 
of a global economic crisis. That has led to increased food donations 
to economically depressed countries and more government-backed loan 
and credit guarantees. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat's gains were limited were expectations the USDA would  
report much of the winter wheat crop remains in good to excellent condition, 
setting the stage for ample supplies amid a time of weak world demand. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for July delivery rose 3/4 cent to $2.86 1/2 a bushel;  
May corn rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.32 1/4 a bushel; May oats rose 4 1/2 
cents to $1.17 1/2 a bushel; May soybeans rose 10 cents to $4.99 1/4 
a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Meat and livestock also rose sharply, on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, after USDA General Sales Manager Christopher Goldthwait said 
South Korea this week likely will sign a $1 billion export credit guarantee 
that would mean more sales of beef and pork this year. 
</P>
<P>
        April live cattle rose .35 cent to 67 cents a pound; April  
feeder cattle rose .27 cent to 71.42 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
rose 1.65 cents to 44.45 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose the limit 
3 cents to 54.45 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
