<HEADLINE> John Hancock Urges IOC Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- John Hancock continued to be the most vocal  
Olympic sponsor about the ongoing bribes scandal, calling on IOC 
member Phil Coles to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt, Mr. Coles has sincere and personal reasons for  
staying,'' the sponsor said in a written statement released Monday. 
``He has made many important contributions to the Olympics over the 
years. But now, he is damaging the movement worldwide as well as 
Australia's outstanding efforts to stage what will be extraordinary 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``By leaving, he can right that unintentional wrong.''  
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said last week he is asking  
Coles, the Australian's ex-wife and Greek Olympic officials for 
more information regarding expensive gifts the Coles were said to 
have received. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgina Coles, who was divorced from Coles almost six years  
ago, sent a fax to IOC officials Friday in which she said the 
couple received a gold-and-diamond necklace and cufflinks while 
visiting Athens, which made an unsuccessful Olympic bid in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The items have been appraised at $6,300 -- far beyond the IOC's  
$150 limit on gifts from bid cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney Morning Herald reported Monday that a Greek jeweler  
has admitted supplying the Athens Olympic bid team with fine 
jewelry, including a gold necklace owned by the wife of Coles. 
</P>
<P>
	Already slapped with a severe censure for accepting lavish  
travel in the Salt Lake City bid scandal, Coles could be expelled 
if the board finds he previously violated the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney Olympics chief Michael Knight has called on Coles to  
``stop the pain'' by quitting the board of SOCOG, the organizing 
committee for the 2000 Games. But Coles said Friday he would not 
resign from the SOCOG board or the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	John Hancock praised the way SOCOG has responded to the scandal.  
</P>
<P>
	``They have been blunt, direct and relentless in pursuing the  
truth and demanding accountability,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Hancock president and chief operations officer David  
D'Alessandro previously said he had seen nothing from the two days 
of Olympic meetings that would cause him to resume TV ad 
negotiations with NBC for the games or return the Olympic rings to 
company reports and billboards, two actions he took as the scandal 
unfolded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
