<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broadcast.com Shares Jump 37 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of Broadcast.com Inc. jumped 37 percent  
Monday following a report that Yahoo! Inc. is in talks to acquire 
the Internet audio and video provider. 
</P>
<P>
	Takeover rumors started Friday with a Business Week Online story  
that said Yahoo! is ``hot to snap up Broadcast.com.'' The report 
cited a source familiar with discussions between the two companies. 
Internet chat rooms picked up the story and have tossed in other 
likely suitors for Broadcast.com. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yahoo! spokeswoman said the company does not comment on market  
speculation. A spokeswoman for Broadcast.com said company 
executives did not know why its stock was up and had no 
announcement to make. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Broadcast.com is perhaps best known for its Webcast  
of Victoria's Secret live fashion show last month. But analysts say 
the online distribution of audio and video on the Internet could 
become a very profitable business as high-speed, also known as 
broadband, access to the Web becomes more widely available. 
</P>
<P>
	That would make Broadcast.com attractive to Yahoo! The Santa  
Clara, Calif., which provides a gateway and search engine for the 
Internet, may be looking to add content to its Web site to attract 
more customers and keep them on the site longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need more features and capabilities,'' said Charles Lax,  
general partner of SoftBank Venture Capital, which is Yahoo!'s 
biggest shareholder. 
</P>
<P>
	Lax said he didn't know if the two companies were in talks. But,  
he added, Broadcast.com would give Yahoo! broadband content, which 
is something Yahoo! doesn't have, but its rival Excite Inc. does. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! wasn't the only name being bandied around as an  
attractive partner for Broadcast.com. Participants in chat rooms on 
the Internet speculated that America Online and General Electric 
Corp., which owns NBC, could also be interested in buying the audio 
and video distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcast.com's stock rose $31.50 to close at $116.50 on heavy  
volume on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Yahoo!'s shares fell $5 to $165, 
also on Nasdaq. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
