<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gwyneth Paltrow Wins Best Actress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gwyneth Paltrow established herself as a fresh, elegant symbol  
of Generation X style, but she won the actress Oscar by going back 
to a much earlier time: 16th century England. She played the 
willowy lover who inspires a youthful Bard in the romantic comedy 
``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Paltrow wasn't the filmmakers' first choice for Viola, the  
playwright's fictional lover and purported inspiration for ``Romeo 
and Juliet.'' She got the part when filming was postponed and the 
cast reorganized around a young, romantic Will. 
</P>
<P>
	Julia Roberts originally was named for the part of Viola.  
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	--From the podium: Shaking slightly and stammering at times, her  
performance at the ceremony was anything but cool and composed. The 
actress sobbed as she thanked everyone from her ``Grandpa Buster'' 
to her ``soulful partner (co-star) Joseph Fiennes.'' ``I would not 
have been able to play this role had I not understood love of a 
tremendous magnitude and for that I thank my family,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hollywood roots: Her father is movie producer Bruce Paltrow and  
her mother is actress Blythe Danner. 
</P>
<P>
	--Early breakthroughs: Her first movie role was in ``Shout'' with  
John Travolta. A chance meeting with Steven Spielberg led to her 
casting as Wendy in his grown-up version of Peter Pan, ``Hook.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Bio: Age 25, born in Los Angeles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
