<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges No NATO Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- On the eve of an important trip to the United  
States, Russia Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov again urged America 
and its allies not to unleash airstrikes against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov would like to concentrate on getting loans for Russia's  
failing economy while in Washington this week. But with the crisis 
in Kosovo seemingly headed for a showdown, the sharp U.S.-Russian 
differences look likely to become the focus of his trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are categorically against the use of force against  
Yugoslavia,'' Primakov told reporters after meeting Monday with 
visiting Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. ``We believe 
that political levers to influence the situation are far from being 
exhausted yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if his departure for the United States might be postponed  
because of the situation in Kosovo, Primakov was evasive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope there will be no raids,'' said Primakov, who was  
scheduled to leave Tuesday for Washington for talks with President 
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has warned it is likely to use force if Yugoslavia does not  
accept an interim political settlement in Kosovo, a province where 
Yugoslav forces are battling ethnic Albanian guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is an ally of Yugoslavia, but has no effective means of  
halting NATO air strikes. Russia also sees NATO and its expansion 
into eastern Europe as a threat to its own security, and bombing 
raids would only further strain frayed relations. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO attacks ``would have an irreparable destabilizing effect on  
the situation in Kosovo, the former Yugoslavia, Europe and the 
whole world,'' Primakov said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian prime minister has been a vocal critic of U.S.  
global dominance. Yet he knows he will need some measure of U.S. 
support if Russia is to win new loans from foreign lenders, 
including the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's deep-rooted economic problems have become even more  
acute since its financial markets imploded last August. Russia 
faces $17.5 billion in foreign debts this year, but can't afford to 
pay more than half that amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is seeking at least $4 billion in new loans from the IMF,  
Russia's Central Bank Chairman Viktor Gerashchenko said Monday. 
However, the IMF has been critical of Russia's economic program. 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov is to meet IMF chief Michel Camdessus in Washington,  
but no decision on Russia's loan bid is expected until after the 
Russian prime minister returns home. 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov's government has stabilized the sinking economy in the  
past few months. The ruble is relatively steady, inflation is down 
to about 4 percent a month and store shelves remained full through 
the winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Gerashchenko acknowledged that the Central Bank's hard  
currency reserves would not be sufficient to keep the ruble stable 
and pay off the country's foreign debts for much longer. 
</P>
<P>
	The reserves stood at $11.4 billion last week, a small sum  
relative to the size of Russia's population and its debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
