<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Majerus Won't Coach San Diego State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Utah's Rick Majerus on Monday night turned down  
San Diego State's offer to take over its moribund men's basketball 
program, a day after Gonzaga's Dan Monson withdrew his name from 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	Majerus had been San Diego State's No. 1 choice since Fred  
Trenkle announced on Feb. 11 that he was resigning at season's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The withdrawal of Majerus and Monson apparently moves former St.  
John's coach Fran Fraschilla to the top of athletic director Rick 
Bay's list, although Bay said he is considering other candidates. 
One of them could be Purdue's Gene Keady. 
</P>
<P>
	Majerus said from Salt Lake City that his decision ``had nothing  
to do with anything other than some personal issues in my life'' 
which he wouldn't elaborate on. 
</P>
<P>
	Bay said Majerus was ``very complimentary'' of the Aztecs'  
offer, but neither man would discuss specifics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could not make as much money as I make at Utah,'' Majerus  
said. ``I turned down a pro job just a couple of weeks ago. If this 
was a money issue, I would go to the pros.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Majerus said he was contacted after Trenkle resigned, but that  
the discussions with San Diego State took place only after Utah was 
eliminated from the second round of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed a little time to sort things out,'' Majerus said.  
</P>
<P>
	That apparently was Monson's reason for pulling his name out of  
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's an excellent job and a great opportunity, but I  
just don't think it's for me at this time,'' Monson said from 
Spokane, Wash. ``I think I have a good situation here and I'm 
emotionally not ready to make a decision like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Monson spoke by phone Sunday with San Diego State athletic  
director Rick Bay. Gonzaga reached the final eight before losing 
67-62 to Connecticut on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego State was 4-22 this year, its fourth losing season in  
five years under Trenkle. The Aztecs have had just one winning 
season since their last NCAA tournament appearance, in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Majerus said the Aztecs' program can be salvaged.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a terrific job,'' he said. ``Whoever gets that  
job will work for a terrific athletic director, a terrific 
president, in a great city with a great environment. That job is a 
good job.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
