<DOCNO> APW19990322.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:52:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Last-Minute Diplomacy in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Declaring ``we are on the brink of  
military action,'' a special U.S. envoy came to Belgrade today in 
an 11th-hour bid to persuade Yugoslavia's president to accept a 
Kosovo peace plan or face NATO attack. 
</P>
<P>
	An attack by NATO forces could come soon after Richard Holbrooke  
wraps up his talks tonight in the Yugoslav capital with hard-line 
leader Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Chances for any agreement appeared bleak. Fighting raged today  
in the Serbian province, with the ethnic Albanian-run Kosovo 
Information Center saying at least five villages were burning in 
the central Drenica region and Lapastica, the rebel headquarters 
for northeastern Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav government showed no sign of dropping its  
opposition to the international peace plan agreed to last week in 
Paris by the ethnic Albanian rebels -- especially for any NATO 
troops sent into Kosovo to police the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Zivadin Jovanovic, the Yugoslav foreign minister, said today  
that ``no pressure can change our principled stand.'' Yugoslavia 
doesn't ``accept foreign troops,'' he said, and if any NATO 
soldiers are sent in, ``of course it will be met by force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jovanovic told CNN ``we are not looking for confrontation'' but  
that his country considers any NATO force sent to Kosovo to be an 
``aggression against a sovereign country, Yugoslavia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American envoy, Holbrooke, stopped in Brussels, Belgium, for  
talks with senior officials from the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Atlantic Council, NATO's top policymaking body, today  
authorized Secretary-General Javier Solana to order airstrikes on 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Solana is conducting a series of consultations with the allies  
before issuing an order for what the council described as ``subject 
to further consultation, on a broader range of air operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials said that means a second phase of air operations  
encompassing a much more diverse list of targets and allowing a 
much more intense pace of operations. Precise details weren't 
known. 
</P>
<P>
	After the NATO visit, Holbrooke warned that if Milosevic does  
not reconsider, ``the consequences will be clear and severe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on the brink of military action,'' Holbrooke said.  
``It's not too late to avoid it, but the window is narrowing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement later to the local independent TV station  
Anem, Holbrooke tried to present the issue of foreign troops in 
Kosovo as something that would benefit Serbs as well as ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a misunderstanding in my view on the part of  
many people in Yugoslavia concerning this force,'' Holbrooke said. 
``I want it to be clear that this force, if the Yugoslav government 
invites them in, will be a force composed of many nations including 
NATO nations, Russia and other countries that would bring peace to 
Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the peacekeeping troops ``would protect both the  
Albanian and Serb communities from the kinds of violence, 
indiscriminate and unnecessary violence, which has been taking 
place in Kosovo recently,'' he said. ``This force would be for the 
benefit of all people in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslavs remained defiant. The Yugoslav army today accused  
the United States of ``saber-rattling,'' and there was no letup in 
the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Battles escalated Saturday after international monitors withdrew  
to Macedonia and the army stepped up its operations against the 
Kosovo Liberation Army. The U.N. relief agency said 25,000 people 
had been driven from their homes in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	Near Srbica, KLA fighters ambushed police today, triggering a  
gunbattle that lasted several hours, witnesses reported. Serb 
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said rebels attacked 
the police station in Malisevo with mortars and automatic weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters saw houses burning in Srbica and talked to ethnic  
Albanians who alleged mass killings by Serb forces, claims that 
could not immediately be verified. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, Holbrooke briefed NATO and European officials about  
his mission. French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said he was not 
optimistic any progress could be made. 
</P>
<P>
	After arriving in Belgrade, Holbrooke went to the Russian  
Embassy to confer with U.S., Russian and European Union mediators 
from last week's failed peace talks. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said Holbrooke would  
be delivering a stark message: ``Move to the path of peace or face 
the punishment of NATO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An allied fleet of warships and attack planes is ready for a  
possible bombardment of Yugoslavia that likely would begin with 
pilotless cruise missiles fired at the country's air defense 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 350-400 allied aircraft are designated for the air  
campaign, in addition to a fleet of U.S. and allied ships. Most are 
stationed at Aviano Air Base in northern Italy. Some are in Germany 
and England. 
</P>
<P>
	Cruise missiles are a weapon of choice for the opening barrage  
of any air campaign because they eliminate the risk of losing 
pilots to Yugoslavia's extensive air defense network. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force B-52s standing by in England are armed with  
air-launched cruise missiles. Other B-1 Lancers and B-2 Spirits 
bombers based in the United States might also see action. 
</P>
<P>
	The peace plan that the Yugoslavs object to calls for 28,000  
NATO troops -- including 4,000 Americans -- to supervise the accord. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2,000 people have died and 300,000 have been driven  
from their homes in a year of conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
