<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed early  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans suffered opening setbacks from Friday's late  
rally, but then recovered on expectations that weekly exports may 
remain relatively strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by prospects the U.S. Agriculture  
Department would report winter wheat conditions remain mostly in 
the good-to-excellent category, at a time when world exports 
continue to be depressed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.87 a bushel; May  
corn was unchanged at $2.29 a bushel; May oats rose 3 1/2 cents to 
$1.16 1/2 a bushel; May soybeans rose 1/4 cent to $4.89 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork bellies futures were higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle and lean hogs were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle rose .10 cent to 66.75 cents a pound; April  
feeder cattle rose .05 cent to 71.20 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
rose .65 cent to 43.45 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose .85 
cent to 52.30 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
