<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	High winds blew through New England Monday while the Plains had  
rain and the Northwest was mostly cloudy. 
</P>
<P>
	The wind gusted to 49 mph in Manchester, N.H., and 46 mph in  
Brunswick, Maine. Earlier in the day, Milton, Maine had a gust of 
77 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind damage, including downed trees and power lines, was  
reported across Connecticut, Rhode Island and Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous flash flood warnings were posted for southern New  
England as a result of heavy rainfall Sunday night and Monday 
morning. Maine had rain most of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Colder air wrapping around the backside of the storm system over  
New England brought snow over areas of the eastern Great Lakes and 
western New England. Snow fell from Vermont and parts of New 
Hampshire, south across New York and Pennsylvania into eastern 
Ohio. Most of the snowfall was light. 
</P>
<P>
	A cool and stable airmass remained in place across much of the  
mid-Atlantic states and Southeast as high pressure continues to 
build. Fair skies were seen from Indiana, through Kentucky, into 
Florida and the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	A stationary frontal boundary stretching across the Plains  
brought rain from Nebraska and Iowa, south and east into Missouri. 
Most of the rain was light. The showers were expected to gradually 
spread east across Iowa and Missouri. Parts of far southwestern 
Illinois may see some showers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and very warm conditions were seen from the lower  
Mississippi Valley into the southern Plains. Temperatures reached 
the 70 degree mark in parts of western Texas. Fair skies and mild 
temperatures were expected to continue across the region through 
the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the western United States was under the influence of  
high pressure. Skies ranged from partly to mostly cloudy across the 
northern Rockies to mostly clear over the Southwest and southern 
Rockies. Clouds were widespread across the Pacific Northwest as a 
cold front approached the region. Rain showers were seen across 
western Washington. They were to spread into western Oregon and 
northwestern California later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	By midday, temperatures around the continental United States  
ranged from 81 in Fort Stockton, Texas to 11 in Hayward, Wis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
