<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Courier, Martin Head Davis Cup Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi will not  
play for the U.S. Davis Cup team in its first-round match. 
</P>
<P>
	So team captain Tom Gullikson hopes his underdog team can draw  
strength from that. 
</P>
<P>
	The squad announced Monday will include Jim Courier, Todd  
Martin, Jan-Michael Gambill and Alex O'Brien against Great Britain 
on April 2-4 in Birmingham, England. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes controversy exacts a positive,'' Gullikson said at a  
news conference during the Lipton Championships. ``It helps make 
you stronger and really increases your resolve to take these guys 
here -- Alex and Jan-Michael, Todd and Jim -- who are really 
committed to it and really go out and give a wonderful 
performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi, angry about the recent firing of the team physician,  
said Saturday he'll never play Davis Cup again. Sampras has been 
criticized for refusing to help the U.S. team in 1998 and again 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really an honor to get to play for your country,''  
O'Brien said. ``I wish the rest of our guys felt that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without Sampras and Agassi, Gullikson acknowledged that the  
British should be favored. Their team will be led by Tim Henman and 
Greg Rusedski. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing at home and they have two top-10 players,''  
Gullikson said. ``So I think the pressure is on them to win the 
match.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Courier and Martin have long, successful histories in Davis Cup,  
and both were part of the U.S. team that won the cup in 1995. 
Courier is 15-9 in Davis Cup competition, and Martin is 13-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Gambill and O'Brien are each 1-1 in cup competition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
