<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Ratings Are Down Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite few close games, CBS' tournament  
coverage is managing to hold its own in the ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	Through Sunday's regional finals, CBS had a 6.0 overnight rating  
and a 13 share, down 3 percent from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think we can make up some ground in the Final Four,'' said  
Mike Aresco, CBS' vice president for programming. ``The ratings 
tell the story of the tournament strength because we've hardly had 
any buzzer-beaters and some blowouts that really don't happen that 
often.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CBS had a 7.8 overnight rating for the four regional finals this  
past weekend, which was up 1 percent from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the four matchups posted gains. The Gonzaga-Connecticut  
game posted a 7.4, up 14 percent from Arizona-Utah in 1998; 
Duke-Temple got a 7.0, 9 percent higher than Stanford-Rhode Island; 
and St. John's-Ohio State received a 8.3, up 1 percent from 
Connecticut-North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The only weekend game that fell was the Michigan State-Kentucky  
matchup, which posted a 8.7, down 12 percent from the Duke-Kentucky 
thriller. 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of TV households in the nation  
tuned to a program, and each point represents 994,000 homes. The 
share is the percentage tuned to a program among those televisions 
on at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
