<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S.C. Gov. Cancels Photo Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Headlines Headlines Headlines .....    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Gov. Jim Hodges, who previously said he  
could not cancel South Carolina's contract to sell nearly 4 million 
driver's license photos for a fraud-prevention system, reversed 
course today and ordered the agreement broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodges said he was persuaded to move when he found out this  
weekend that 4,200 photos of children as young as 10 had been 
transmitted to Image Data LLC of Nashua, N.H. The children's photos 
are from Public Safety Department identity cards. 
</P>
<P>
	``South Carolinians have spoken clearly that they want these  
records to be kept private and we as state government must move 
forward to do that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Image Data's president said the company had not decided whether  
to sue, but Hodges said he was willing to take that risk. The 
company has paid $6,000 of the $27,000 it owes and will be 
reimbursed, Public Safety Director Boykin Rose said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are obviously disappointed at Governor Hodges' recent  
action,'' company President Bob Houvener said. 
</P>
<P>
	Image Data also bought driver's license photos from Florida and  
Colorado. The company challenged a temporary restraining order on 
the sale of license photos in Florida. Colorado stopped selling 
license photos while the Legislature considers outlawing sales of 
personal information. 
</P>
<P>
	Image Data's fraud-prevention system briefly shows merchants the  
picture of a credit card holder or check writer. The company says 
the pictures are encoded so they cannot be saved or otherwise 
transmitted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
