<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 15:13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oscars Weren't Huge TV Hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Academy Awards can't have titanic television  
ratings every year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratings for Sunday night's long-winded Oscar telecast sank 18  
percent from 1998, when the box office blockbuster ``Titanic'' 
helped give the telecast its highest Nielsen Media Research numbers 
since 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The show had a 28.6 household rating and a 46 share. The  
telecast, which stretched over four hours, had an average audience 
of 45.6 million viewers, down from the 55.2 million viewers of 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second-lowest rated Oscar telecast since 1991. The  
1997 broadcast, when ``The English Patient'' was named best 
picture, had a 27.4 rating. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC said they expected the numbers to drop since big winners  
``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' weren't as 
popular as ``Titanic.'' But executives said they had a 15 percent 
increase in younger viewers this year over the 1997 telecast, 
meaning many of the young people drawn in last year came back. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew that last year was a home run because of `Titanic' and  
those type of Academy Awards are few and far between,'' said Larry 
Hyams, ABC's vice president of audience analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	The network hoped that moving the Oscar telecast from Monday to  
Sunday night would give the ratings a boost, but that appeared to 
make little difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a few ears remained singed Monday from host Whoopi  
Goldberg's blue-tinted jokes and a Joan Rivers tirade over her 
access to stars on an E! Entertainment Television Oscar pre-show 
telecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldberg raised a few eyebrows with her jokes, including several  
references to sex and bodily functions. Larry Marino, host of 
``Morning Magazine'' on KIEV, a conservative-leaning AM radio talk 
station in Los Angeles, said he got a lot of negative calls this 
morning about the Oscars and Goldberg's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We couldn't get them all on,'' Marino said. ``In my opinion,  
her jokes were sophomoric and much like you would hear from 
15-year-olds in a bus back from the day at the beach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An ABC executive in charge of specials said the network felt  
``very positive'' about Goldberg's performance and said it was 
harsh to judge her on the basis of a few lines in a four-hour show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoopi is a stand-up comedian,'' said Michael Davies,  
executive vice president for alternative series and special 
programming. ``I don't think it was that different from the last 
time we had seen her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, whose pre-Oscar telecast asking stars about their  
wardrobes has quickly become an awards show staple, was seething 
Sunday night about ABC hampering her access to the stars. For the 
first time, ABC showed an Oscar-sanctioned pre-show of its own. 
</P>
<P>
	``ABC is hogging everything. ... They're being very naughty,''  
Rivers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davies wouldn't second-guess the people who run the Oscars for  
the show's length. At just over four hours, ending past 12:30 a.m. 
Monday on the East Coast, it was the longest Academy Award telecast 
ever. 
</P>
<P>
	In rehearsals, the show timed out at 3 1/2 hours, which Davies said  
is the ideal length. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just the nature of live television,'' he said.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
