<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners' Davis Improves on Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- After setting a club record with 34 errors  
last season, Seattle third baseman Russ Davis knew he had to do 
work on his defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I jumped the rope a little bit here and there. I did some box  
drills, jumping back and forth here and there,'' he said. ``But I'm 
not going to sit here and tell you I went home and killed myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Improvement has been noticeable this spring. He didn't make his  
first error of the spring until Monday, an 11-9 loss to the Chicago 
White Sox that included his fifth homer of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	``He worked on his agility,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``He  
gets himself in a better position now. He's got more range. There's 
never been anything wrong with his hands. His body just wasn't in 
position before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a lineup featuring All-Stars Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex  
Rodriguez, Davis is another strong offensive player, matching his 
career high with 20 homers and driving in a career-best 82 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	But his fielding was so bad that Piniella took him off third  
base -- where he wound up making 32 errors in 137 games -- and put 
him in left field -- where he made two errors in three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five of Davis' error came before the All-Star break.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm real happy with the way I finished up with my defense last  
year,'' Davis said. ``I finished real strong. So far so good this 
spring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners' defense was 12th in the AL as Seattle slumped to a  
76-85 record, 11 1/2 games behind first-place Texas in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was awful,'' Davis said. ``But I know if we would have been  
winning that half, the things that were said wouldn't have been 
brought up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis has come up with a new strategy to keep his mental health  
intact: He doesn't plan to read any newspapers, listen to any radio 
stations or watch any TV. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I do good, I'll forget about it,'' he said. ``Yesterday was  
yesterday. If I do bad, yesterday was yesterday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners are counting on getting a big year from Davis, who  
came to them in a trade that sent Tino Martinez and Jeff Nelson to 
the New York Yankees in December 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, 29, thinks he can have his best season. And that includes  
his defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think mechanically there's a whole lot wrong with what  
I do out there,'' he said. ``My feet move around good. My hands are 
in good position. I think the main thing for me is just to stay 
focused. My concentration should be there for every pitch.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
