<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall in Light Trading / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *With BC-Bonds-Glance    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds fell Monday, retreating for a second  
session as traders braced for the sale of $21 billion in new debt 
securities from the government and AT&AMP;T later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1/4 point,  
or $2.50 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 5.57 percent from 5.55 percent late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	With no major economic news to steer the market, traders were  
awaiting Tuesday's pricing of a record $7 billion in bonds being 
sold by AT&AMP;T Corp. and Wednesday's government auction of $14 
billion in new two-year Treasury notes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell between 1/16 and 3/32 point from late Friday, while 
intermediate maturities fell between 3/32 and 3/16 point, reported 
Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, fell 3.57 
points to 1,282.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 4.51 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from late Friday to 4.40 
percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.64 percent, as the discount 
rose 0.02 percentage point to 4.47 percent. One-year yields were 
unchanged at 4.71 percent, while the discount held steady at late 
Friday's 4.49 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.81 percent from late Friday's 4.75 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 to 125 1/8. The average yield to 
maturity was unchanged from late Friday's 5.17 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
