<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gen. Westmoreland Donates Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Retired Army Gen. William Westmoreland,  
who commanded U.S. troops in the Vietnam War, donated hundreds of 
thousands of personal papers and hundreds of books to the 
University of South Carolina today. 
</P>
<P>
	Westmoreland, who turns 85 Friday, was joined by family and  
friends at a luncheon where university officials announced the 
donation. 
</P>
<P>
	Westmoreland's collection, including a 700-volume library, will  
become part of the South Caroliniana Library collection. The 
Spartanburg native who now lives in Charleston said he wanted the 
collection to go to a university in his native state. 
</P>
<P>
	The collection of documents, which if put in cardboard boxes  
end-to-end would stretch 150 feet, will take about two years to 
catalogue, said Herbert Hartsook, the library's curator of modern 
political collections. 
</P>
<P>
	George Terry, vice-provost and dean of university libraries,  
said the collection will be an important resource for historians 
studying the Vietnam era. It also includes correspondence relating 
to Westmoreland's later libel suit against CBS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
