<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals' Morris To Miss Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Matt Morris, expected to be the ace of the St.  
Louis Cardinals pitching staff, will miss the entire season because 
of a torn ligament in his right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris was examined Sunday by Dr. Frank Jobe and will require  
ligament replacement surgery, a procedure Jobe pioneered 25 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tough break for him and for us,'' Cardinals manager Tony La  
Russa said. ``You just don't replace a Matt Morris.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old right-hander was 7-5 with a team-leading 2.53  
ERA last season, missing all but one start in the first half 
because of a shoulder surgery. He was bothered arm stiffness this 
spring, threw two scoreless innings against Kansas City in his 
first start, then felt pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He put in a lot of work in the offseason on his shoulder, and  
then something like this,'' La Russa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, 12-9 with a 3.19 ERA two years ago in his rookie season,  
joined a growing list of prominent NL Central pitchers with arm 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago Cubs ace Kerry Wood, the NL Rookie of the Year, will  
miss the season because of a torn elbow ligament. Cincinnati Reds 
ace Denny Neagle may start the season on the disabled list because 
of a chronic shoulder problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals are also without another promising young pitcher,  
Alan Benes. Benes, 27, missed all of last season after rotator cuff 
surgery. He had additional surgery in September, and the team isn't 
sure when he'll return. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other guys will have to step up,'' Benes said. ``Matt  
Morris was a big part of our staff. We feel terrible for him. But 
we still have a talented staff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donovan Osborne, who has been on the disabled list a number of  
times himself over the past several seasons, appears likely to 
become the Cardinals' No. 1 starter, 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Mercker, Kent Bottenfield and Darren Oliver also are  
expected to start. The fifth starter will likely be either Manny 
Aybar, impressive at Triple-A but is 8-10 with a 5.18 ERA in parts 
of two big league seasons, or rookie Jose Jimenez, 3-0 with a 2.95 
ERA during a September callup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
