<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 13:25:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Book: IRS Whistle-Blowers Hounded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Agents who blew the whistle on abusive  
practices at the IRS are suffering reprisals, says a Republican 
senator whose hearings led to the law aimed at reform. 
</P>
<P>
	In a book he wrote to keep the heat on the Internal Revenue  
Service even as it implements changes, Sen. William Roth of 
Delaware says there is continuing evidence of an ingrained culture 
of taxpayer abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Changing the culture of the IRS will require more than  
legislation,'' wrote Roth, chairman of the Senate Finance 
Committee. ``It will take a decade of training and oversight, 
vigilance by Congress and zero tolerance for abuse and 
mismanagement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Finance Committee's high-profile hearings on taxpayer horror  
stories led to last year's sweeping IRS reform law giving Americans 
more rights and improving oversight of the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``The Power to Destroy,'' Roth and co-author William Nixon  
said that despite IRS pledges that it wouldn't happen, several 
agency witnesses who testified about problems appear to be 
suffering reprisals on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been deeply disturbed to hear from several that they  
are being hounded by their superiors,'' Roth wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	One unnamed employee in the IRS examinations branch is quoted in  
the book as telling Roth she has gotten failing grades on 
evaluations since the hearings, compared with ``good to superior'' 
for 15 years prior to that. The employee's bosses also have 
intervened in some of her tax cases, something she said never 
happened before. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to build a case against me, to get rid of me,''  
Roth quotes the woman as telling him recently. ``Once I contacted 
people outside the agency, things started falling apart for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon said in an interview that IRS Commissioner Charles  
Rossotti met last week with him and Roth to discuss the reprisal 
allegations. IRS spokesman Steve Pyrek confirmed the meeting, and 
Rossotti said in a brief interview Monday that the agency will 
enforce ``specific instructions'' against any retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've done everything that's humanly possible to make sure  
those employees are treated fairly and we will continue to do 
that,'' Rossotti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth wrote that Congress should take further steps to make sure  
IRS employees aren't held to a Mafia-like ``omerta'' code of 
silence so they can ``share information necessary for appropriate 
oversight and reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book also discloses IRS in-house surveys of 80,000 employees  
in 1995 and 1997. These surveys found that 30 percent had observed 
at least one instance of ``unfair or uncaring'' treatment of a 
taxpayer, while 13 percent had seen such abuse at least three 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, 15 percent said they knew of agents ``lying or  
misleading'' a taxpayer to force compliance, while 19 percent had 
seen situations where taxpayers with political clout were given 
preferential treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth said these problems stemmed from intense pressure on agents  
to meet now-scrapped numerical enforcement quotas in an agency 
shrouded by secrecy. 
</P>
<P>
	``For too many decades, power and insufficient accountability  
have corrupted,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The book has nothing but praise for Rossotti, who left a  
computer and consulting business he founded to take over the IRS in 
mid-1997. Roth wrote that Rossotti ``can do great things to correct 
the service from the inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An IRS statement in response to Roth's book says the service has  
``made substantial progress'' in changing how it deals with 
taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IRS clearly received its marching orders, and we took them  
seriously,'' the statement says. ``Much more remains to be done, 
and we are committed to that end.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
