<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Republic Gets New Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New Republic, struggling to maintain its  
niche in the increasingly crowded business of political commentary, 
is getting a new look. 
</P>
<P>
	``The magazine as it is now is a pretty gray production,''  
editor Charles Lane said Monday from Washington. ``We wanted to 
reach out to folks who are used to seeing something brighter in 
what they read. ... It's going to be a younger look.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 85-year-old magazine -- once solidly on the political left  
but now offering a more centrist Democratic perspective -- hopes its 
sharper image will boost newsstand sales. With an ocean of 
political opinion available on cable television, Internet chat 
sites and elsewhere in the print media, editors worry The New 
Republic's voice may be drowned out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a more competitive environment,'' said publisher Will  
Lippincott. ``Especially the last year, during the Monica Lewinsky 
scandal, everyone had an opinion and everyone wanted to share it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The redesign, which will debut in the magazine's April 12 issue,  
will not affect editorial content, Lane said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to start doing fashion,'' he said. ``Our  
magazine, even as it's getting a brighter package, wants to be a 
place where thoughtful people come to have their assumptions 
challenged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Editors plan to lighten text-heavy pages with color -- until now  
reserved only for the magazine's cover -- as well as more and larger 
illustrations and photos. Cover art will be brighter and the 
magazine's title will have a new, bolder typeface, Lane said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fair to say that we made a concession to a more visual  
age,'' Lippincott said. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Republic, which touts itself as a weekly forum for  
iconoclastic, intellectually original opining, has a circulation 
that has long hovered around 100,000, and often loses money, said 
owner Martin Peretz. Recent losses have run as high as $500,000 
annually, but Peretz said he expects to break even this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine has lost a string of top editors in recent years,  
and was forced to apologize to readers last summer after 
discovering that a former associate editor invented all or part of 
27 articles he wrote for the publication. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the troubles, those at the magazine say The New  
Republic's quality and independent voice separate it from the 
shrill, superficial analysis offered in other quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't make it easy,'' Peretz said. ``These are articles  
that furrow the brow. You puzzle over them. ... There isn't a lot 
that's obvious in The New Republic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the editor of The Nation, a liberal weekly competitor, said  
The New Republic's long-running drift toward the political center 
might make it harder to appeal to readers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nation ``meets needs that aren't being answered in the  
mainstream press,'' said Katrina Vanden Heuvel. ``The New Republic 
is trying to compete more with the newsweeklies by virtue of this 
redesign -- Time, Newsweek -- and I worry that it might lose its 
mandate as a publication of ideas. ... I think the magazine today 
is unclear about what its role is.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
