<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Refugees Seek Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIANAK, Indonesia (AP) -- Sleeping on palm mats in a sports  
stadium, more than 2,000 people left homeless by fighting took 
refuge here today from violence in Borneo that has left more than 
100 dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the Madurese refugees said they were too frightened to  
return to their villages after the brutal assaults, in which 
fighters from other ethnic groups paraded at times with severed 
heads and other grisly tokens from the slaughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so scared by the attacks on our people, and I lost my  
husband in the chaos,'' said Ni'mah, 35, a mother of four children, 
including a son she gave birth to during the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Holding her 2-day-old boy, Ni'mah said she last saw her husband,  
Mahari, moments before troops evacuated her from their village, 
Seungian. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she hadn't even been able to give her new son a name  
since fleeing their home and losing her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 15,000 Madurese have fled their villages in cars,  
boats or military trucks. Some 2,200 of them took refuge in 
Pontianak sports stadium along with some 5,000 others elsewhere in 
the city, located on Borneo's western coast, 385 miles northeast of 
Jakarta, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic violence has consumed the coastal region of Borneo, a  
large island shared by both Indonesia and Malaysia, since armed 
gangs of ethnic Malay, Dayak and Bugis men set upon the Madurese 
immigrants from the island of Madura early last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports on the death toll have differed. A top police source in  
Tabas district, one of the hardest-hit areas, said in an interview 
that 165 people have been killed, 90 percent of them Madurese. He 
spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian media gave other death tolls: Kompas newspaper  
said 110 people have died. The ruling party newspaper, Suara Karya, 
put the death toll at 104. And the evening daily Berita Buana said 
more than 200 have died and about 23,000 have been left homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been very difficult to get an exact death toll because so  
many of the bodies have been dismembered,'' Taslim, an official in 
Singkawang town, said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, the Indonesian military has stayed clear of  
the fighting raging close to the Malaysian border, about 100 miles 
north of Pontianak. 
</P>
<P>
	At the heart of the violence in Sambas town and surrounding  
villages, hundreds of euphoric warriors -- some wearing shirts 
stained with victims' blood -- looted and burned abandoned homes. 
</P>
<P>
	A chunk of flesh dangled by a string from the spear of one  
fighter and a few men carried pieces of scalp. At street 
intersections, cheering crowds assembled to view the severed heads 
of Madurese men. 
</P>
<P>
	Old customs of tribal warfare that were thriving when British  
and Dutch colonists ventured into the Borneo interior centuries ago 
were being played out in gruesome shows of public rejoicing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
