<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Lawyer Claims Juror Bias </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal judge today refused to  
dismiss a juror whose impartiality had been questioned by attorneys 
for Whitewater figure Susan McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's trial was put on hold so District Judge George  
Howard Jr. could consider the defense's motion to remove juror 
Charles Adams from the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	In the judge's chambers, Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos,  
played a scratchy audiotape that he said was recorded off her 
father's answering machine. On it, Geragos said, a local jail 
chaplain claimed that a friend of hers had heard from a friend of 
his that one of the jurors was biased against Mrs. McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is triple hearsay!'' complained Whitewater assistant  
prosecutor Mark Barrett. ``There is no indication of any taint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Geragos, Adams expressed disdain for President  
Clinton and for Mrs. McDougal, a partner of Clinton in the 
Whitewater land development. 
</P>
<P>
	In questioning for jury selection, Adams said he had not formed  
an opinion of Mrs. McDougal. His sister, Evelyn Gentry, told the 
court that Adams had a negative opinion of Clinton, but had not 
indicated an opinion of Mrs. McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard refused to question Adams, however, and directed Geragos  
to file a formal motion if he wanted to pursue his complaint. ``I'm 
not about to let the system be manipulated,'' the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, one of the alternate jurors was dismissed because of  
ties between her family and the prosecution and defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's jury trial on charges of criminal contempt and  
obstruction of justice entered its third week Monday. Her refusal 
to answer questions in front of a federal grand jury about Clinton 
and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton led to criminal charges 
against her. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos said Monday that he will probably call three witnesses  
before Mrs. McDougal takes the stand. He said he may ask her the 
same questions she refused to answer for the grand jury Sept. 4, 
1996, and April 23, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal has said she refused to answer the questions  
because she believed Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr would 
twist her words if she didn't say what he wanted to hear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
