<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jug Wine Sales Down in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Jug wine shipments from California wineries  
were down in 1998, but a boom in premium varietals more than made 
up for it, the Wine Institute reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Total sales of California wines in the United States and abroad  
was about 437 million gallons in 1998, a 3 percent increase over 
the previous year. Most of that wine was purchased in the United 
States -- 338 million gallons -- giving California wines 73 percent 
of the domestic market, institute figures show. 
</P>
<P>
	The estimated retail value of the state's wine shipments  
domestically was $12 billion, up 5 percent from 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Premium California table wine shipments to the United States  
were up 8 percent last year, to 75.1 million cases. Jug wines, 
meanwhile, fell 3 percent, to 67.8 million cases over the previous 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``American consumers are moving upscale to high-end varietal  
wines, shifting their preferences away from many white and blush 
jug wines, which declined in food stores last year,'' said industry 
analyst Jon Fredrikson of Gomberg, Fredrikson &AMP; Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	California wines most in demand were aged reds and wines in  
limited production. Wines priced at $7 and up was the 
fastest-growing segment, up 14 percent. While those pricier wines 
represented only 19 percent of the state's wine gallonage, they 
generated 44 percent of table wine revenues, the institute said. 
</P>
<P>
	Total 1998 wine sales in the United States from all sources was  
up 1 percent over 1997, to about 531 million gallons. The estimated 
retail value was up 5.5 percent, to $17 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
