<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Fall in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Consumer prices in recession-mired Hong Kong  
fell for a fourth consecutive month in February, the government 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The territory's Consumer Price Index fell 1.7 percent compared  
with February 1998, following year-on-year drops of 1.1 percent in 
January and 1.6 percent in December, a statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The past four months are the first time Hong Kong has  
experienced deflation since the government began keeping such price 
statistics in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said Hong Kong people paid less money for  
clothing, shoes, durable goods, food and housing last month. 
Clothing prices fell by a staggering 18.5 percent. Prices were 
higher for alcohol, tobacco, transportation, fuel and light. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail discounts accounted for the sharper fall in prices in the  
period, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The falling prices are not good news for the territory which is  
mired in its worst recession in years. Unemployment is also at a 
record high 6.0 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
