<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vivendi Buying U.S. Filter Corp. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALM DESERT, Calif. (AP) -- Vivendi SA is buying U.S. Filter  
Corp. for about $6.2 billion in cash, enabling the French 
conglomerate to get a stronger foothold in the U.S. water market. 
</P>
<P>
	The transaction announced today would be the largest French  
acquisition ever made in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would have more than $12 billion in annual  
revenue and the deal would nearly double revenues of Vivendi's 
water treatment business, Generale des Eaux, based in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal approved by boards of both companies, Vivendi  
would pay $31.50 per share of U.S. Filter common stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is subject to regulatory approval in the United States  
and Europe. U.S. Filter would become a wholly-owned subsidiary of 
Vivendi. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we recognize is that we share a vision of a full-service,  
global water enterprise,'' said Jean-Marie Messier, chairman of 
Vivendi. ``The world's population is continuing to grow. Industry 
is demanding ever-higher standards of processed water for 
manufacturing and the demand for quality wastewater treatment to 
protect the environment has never been greater.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Filter Chairman Richard J. Heckmann will serve on the board  
of directors for Generale des Eaux and become a member of the 
Vivendi water group executive committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Generale des Eaux provides water treatment services to more than  
25 million people and wastewater treatment services for 16 million 
residents. Worldwide, the Vivendi subsidiary provides services to 
65 million people on every continent. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to its water treatment business, Vivendi owns 34  
percent to French pay-TV operator Canal Plus and has interests in 
telecommunications. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Filter purchased Culligan Water Technologies in February  
1998 for about $1.5 billion in stock. In 1997, U.S. Filter made 
numerous acquisitions, most notably purchasing Memtec Ltd., an 
Australian maker of water filters, for about $399 million in stock. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
