<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weiss Gets First Quadruple Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- This is just what Michael Weiss needed  
going into the World Figure Skating Championships -- his first clean 
quadruple jump in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was good to get that monkey off my back,'' said Weiss, who  
leads an American men 's contingent that looks stronger than 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's usual strength in the pairs also came under challenge  
Monday, as China's Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo were close behind world 
champions Yelena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze in the short 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	American pairs were weak: the highest placement was Kyoko Ina  
and John Zimmerman in eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	As impressive as the quad was as a personal mark for Weiss, its  
drama was upstaged by fellow American Tim Goebel, who hit the first 
quad salchow ever accomplished in the world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Goebel had previously landed the jump at the Goodwill Games and  
the junior Grand Prix finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Registering it at the world championships raises a challenge to  
others. The salchow is more difficult than the quad toe loops 
because the skater does not use the toe pick to boost his launch. 
</P>
<P>
	Four other skaters also managed quads, which just three years  
ago were very rare: China's Guo Zhengxin, Anthony Liu of Australia, 
Russia's Yevgeny Plushenko and Canada's Elvis Stojko, who still 
seemed troubled by a year-old groin injury. 
</P>
<P>
	But amid the cavalcade of quads, one of the top performances of  
the day came from a man who didn't even try one, Alexei Yagudin of 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Yagudin placed at the top of one of the two qualifying groups by  
concentrating on executing lesser jumps with great precision, 
although he did hit one triple-triple combination. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he'd done a quad and a quad-triple in practice the day  
before, Yagudin said he didn't want to take risks in the qualifier, 
partly because he was nursing a sore calf and partly because he 
dislikes the new regime under which the qualifying round counts for 
20 percent of the final score. 
</P>
<P>
	``We decided not to skate the full routine two times,'' he said.  
``This is too stupid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Plushenko at the top of one qualifying group, Yagudin at  
the other and Alexei Urmanov just behind Yagudin, the Russians go 
into the final rounds in a strong position. 
</P>
<P>
	Many have speculated the Russian troika would sweep the medals,  
but Yagudin predicted Russians would take no more than two and that 
Weiss was likely to be the spoiler. Weiss was second behind 
Plushenko in his group, followed by Stojko. Takeshi Honda of Japan 
was third in the other group behind Yagudin and Urmanov. 
</P>
<P>
	In the pairs short program, Berezhnaya streaked a remarkably  
long distance through the air in a throw triple and the performance 
was marred only by side-by-side spins that were a bit out of synch. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a showing that reaffirmed Sikhuralidze's belief that  
Russians and figure-skating have a special relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, the Russian personality, the Russian mind, is really  
close to figure-skating, because in Russia we have nice ballet, 
nice theater,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shen and Zhao drew gasps of both delight and dismay -- the former  
coming with a lovely delayed double twist in which Shen seemed to 
hang in suspended animation, the latter when she put her hands to 
the ice coming out of a throw triple loop. 
</P>
<P>
	Poland's Dorota Zagorska and Mariuz Siudek were in third place  
at the end of the short program. 
</P>
<P>
	Current U.S. champions Danielle and Steve Hartsell, plagued by  
falls, ended in 13th place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 12:53:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Begin Settlement Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. expects to begin negotiations  
with the government soon in an effort to settle its landmark 
antitrust case, but the sides remain far apart on core issues after 
almost five months of an acrimonious courtroom fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The company indicated anew Monday that it would consider  
changing some of its most controversial agreements with the 
nation's computer makers and Internet providers. But the software 
giant won't accept government-demanded restrictions on what new 
features it can add to its Windows operating system software, which 
runs roughly 90 percent of the world's personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	No negotiations have been scheduled, people close to the case  
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft believes it has established a strong legal record on  
the key issues, but also thinks settling the case would be good for 
everyone, including the industry and consumers, said a company 
official who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The company considers itself under orders from the judge to  
explore a settlement. When the trial broke last month for a 
six-week recess, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson 
privately urged lawyers for both sides to use their time wisely. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is expected to resume no earlier than April 12.  
</P>
<P>
	The government has not received any settlement proposal from  
Microsoft, said Assistant Attorney General Joel I. Klein, head of 
the Justice Department's antitrust division. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Justice Department has always been and remains open to a  
settlement that fully protects consumers and assures that similar 
antitrust violations do not occur in the future,'' Klein said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	An effort to reach a compromise last May broke down, and  
Microsoft already has started to formulate plans to appeal a trial 
verdict. Jackson probably will rule this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're very tough negotiators and will not give unless they  
think they have to give,'' predicted Marc Schildkraut, a Washington 
lawyer who negotiated with Microsoft during an antitrust 
investigation when he worked at the Federal Trade Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges that Microsoft wields its considerable  
influence to force other companies into restrictive agreements to 
exclude potential competitors. These contracts, for example, limit 
the ways computer-makers can modify the Windows software sold with 
their computers. Others limit ways Internet companies can promote 
or distribute rival browser software. 
</P>
<P>
	The Microsoft official indicated again Monday that it is willing  
to change some ways it does business with other technology 
companies, including computer manufacturers and Internet providers, 
to address the government's concerns about its contract language. 
At the same time, the official said that any settlement must 
preserve the company's ability to innovate and add new features to 
its products. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also charges that Microsoft uses its market  
dominance to maintain what it describes as monopoly power and to 
extend its influence into emerging areas of technology. For 
example, the company established the popularity of its own Internet 
browser software after bundling it with newer versions of Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week, Microsoft introduced a new version of its  
Internet software that lets customers listen to digital radio 
broadcasts while browsing the Web, similar to rival technology 
already offered by Seattle-based RealNetworks Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial hasn't hurt Microsoft's stock. Since the government  
filed its antitrust lawsuit last May, the price has more than 
doubled in value. 
</P>
<P>
	The key players for any talks will be in Washington this week.  
Attorneys general for the 19 states suing Microsoft with Justice 
expect to be here for a previously scheduled conference. Microsoft 
Chairman Bill Gates also is visiting on a book tour, although he 
isn't planning to meet with government lawyers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990322.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:26:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Duke Is a Big Betting Favorite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- This city's oddsmakers aren't taking any  
chances with Duke's chances of winning a national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Devils are such a prohibitive favorite in Las Vegas  
sports books that bettors would have to wager $7 for every dollar 
they could win on Duke winning its last two games. 
</P>
<P>
	Odds vary at each sports book, but most have had to make Duke  
such a big favorite to try to discourage bets on the Blue Devils 
and get some money bet on the other three teams in the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the biggest favorites we've ever had,'' said  
Pete Korner, who helps set odds for sports books at Las Vegas 
Sports Consultants. ``We're just trying to get some money on the 
other teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Korner opened Duke at a 1-3 favorite, but most sports books went  
well beyond that. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Las Vegas Hilton, bettors wanting to put money on Duke on  
Monday found the Blue Devils a 1-7 favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not getting that many bets on Duke now,'' book manager  
Chuck Esposito said. 
</P>
<P>
	With Duke the heavy favorite, bettors can get 9-2 on Connecticut  
winning the title, 10-1 on Michigan State and 12-1 on Ohio State at 
the Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Duke is such a big favorite because the public wants to see if  
they can keep winning like they have,'' Esposito said. ``They 
really haven't been tested in the second half of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duke is listed as an 11 1/2-point favorite in Saturday's semifinal  
against Michigan State, while Connecticut is a 5 1/2-point favorite 
over Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA tournament generally is a big betting event at casino  
sports books, second in total volume only to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the tournament began, bettors could wager not only on  
individual games but on which team would win the national 
championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
