</P>
<P>
	Broadcast.com Shares Jump 37 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of Broadcast.com Inc. jumped 37 percent  
today following a report that Yahoo! Inc. is in talks to acquire 
the Internet audio and video provider. Takeover rumors started 
Friday with a Business Week Online story that said Yahoo! is ``hot 
to snap up Broadcast.com.'' The report cited a source familiar with 
discussions between the two companies. Internet chat rooms picked 
up the story and have tossed in other likely suitors for 
Broadcast.com. Broadcast.com's stock rose $31.50 to close at 
$116.50 on heavy volume on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Yahoo! shares 
fell $5 to $165, also on the Nasdaq. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Lists New Targets in Beef War  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States announced today it was  
preparing a new list of sanction targets to retaliate against 
Europe's refusal to allow the sale of American beef treated with 
growth hormones. The preliminary target list covers more than $900 
million in European imports, primarily farm products. The 
sanctions, which would effectively double the price of the products 
in the American market, would go into effect at the latest by early 
July, administration officials said in making the announcement. The 
new target list is in addition to $520 million in European products 
targeted in the earlier trade fight involving European restrictions 
on banana shipments by American companies. 

</P>
<P>
	OPEC Cuts Prompt Gas Price Hike  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- OPEC's plan to reduce the world's oil  
supply by about 2.6 percent has already translated into a spike in 
prices at gasoline pumps in the United States and elsewhere. Formal 
approval of the production cuts at the group's meeting tomorrow 
would push gasoline prices even higher, analysts say. OPEC is 
widely expected to approve cuts in oil output totaling 2.1 million 
barrels a day. The average price of all grades of gasoline at U.S. 
service stations surged nearly 8 1/2 cents per gallon over the past 
two weeks, according to the Lundberg Survey, the steepest and 
fastest increase since Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990. 

</P>
<P>
	Vivendi Buying U.S. Filter Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	PALM DESERT, Calif. (AP) -- Vivendi SA is buying U.S. Filter  
Corp. for about $6.2 billion in cash, enabling the French 
conglomerate to get a stronger foothold in the U.S. water market. 
The transaction announced today would be the largest French 
acquisition ever made in the United States. The combined company 
would have more than $12 billion in annual revenue and the deal 
would nearly double revenues of Vivendi's water treatment business, 
Generale des Eaux, based in Paris. The deal is subject to 
regulatory approval in the United States and Europe. U.S. Filter 
would become a wholly-owned subsidiary of Vivendi. 

</P>
<P>
	EU To Pick New Chief Executive  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union leaders will be under  
pressure to name a new chief executive this week to begin repairing 
the damage caused by the sudden resignation of the group's senior 
officials. The EU was thrown into turmoil last week after Jacques 
Santer, head of the group's executive Commission, and 19 other 
senior officials abruptly resigned following a report alleging 
fraud and cronyism in their ranks. Former Italian Prime Minister 
Romano Prodi has emerged as the front-runner to succeed Santer, a 
former prime minister of Luxembourg. Prodi has said he is ready to 
take the job but only for a full five-year term. Santer's outgoing 
commission was due to step down Dec. 31. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Seek To Curb Tax Shelters  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is proposing new  
penalties and increased scrutiny of corporate tax shelters that rob 
the government of billions of dollars a year, Deputy Treasury 
Secretary Lawrence Summers said today. The Treasury Department 
plans as early as next month to release a major paper outlining the 
scope of the tax shelter problem. To create ``real financial 
risks'' for people who devise and use tax shelters, Summers said, 
the administration wants Congress to approve a 25 percent excise 
tax on promoter and lawyer fees. In addition, an unspecified excise 
tax would be imposed on contingency fees, sometimes used when part 
of the deal depends upon a favorable ruling by the Internal Revenue 
Service. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Orders Gucci, LVMH To Talk  
</P>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A Dutch court ruled today that  
fashion group Gucci NV must negotiate with French luxury goods 
maker LVMH Moet Hennessey Louis Vuitton over LVMH's $7.86 billion 
hostile takeover bid. The court in Holland, where Gucci is based, 
also upheld an agreement between Gucci and French retailer 
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute in which PPR will take a 40 percent 
interest in the company. But the court suspended any parts of the 
agreement that would hamper the negotiations between Gucci and 
LVMH. Gucci stocks rose 2 1/8 today at 83 1/8 while LVMH stocks fell 1/4 at 
50 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	SEC Proposes Mutual Fund Changes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to better protect the millions of  
Americans who invest in mutual funds, the government's top 
securities regulator today proposed changes that would enhance the 
power of independent directors of fund companies. Arthur Levitt, 
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, proposed that 
the boards of mutual fund companies have a majority of independent 
directors, that current independent directors rather than fund 
company managers nominate new independent directors and that 
attorneys be available to directors who also are independent from 
company management. 

</P>
