<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Hear Siblings Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A 4-year-old's battle to grow up in the same home  
as his older sister has ended with the U.S. Supreme Court's refusal 
to take up the question of whether siblings put up for adoption 
have the right to stay together. 
</P>
<P>
	The children in the case were known in court papers as ``Hugo''  
and ``Gloria'' to protect their identities. They were said to be so 
close that 6-year-old Gloria translated for her developmentally 
disabled brother when his speech was unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's decision Monday means the boy will likely remain in  
the New Jersey home where he has been living for the last two 
months, while his sister grows up 200 miles away in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	They lived together with a foster mother in Boston for about two  
years before they were separated in January under a ruling by the 
state's high court. An aunt from New Jersey won custody of Hugo, 
while his sister remained in Boston with the foster mother, who has 
adopted her. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the boy appealed to the Supreme Court to reunite  
brother and sister. A ruling in favor of the boy could have 
reunited some 35,000 siblings in similar situations nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Without comment, the high court refused to hear the case.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad this separation will be permanent, that they won't be  
able to grow up together as brother and sister,'' said Susan 
Dillard, a lawyer for Hugo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Massachusetts Social Services Department had supported Hugo  
as his case moved through the state's courts because ``it was in 
his best interest to remain with his sister,'' department 
spokeswoman Lorraine Carli said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the department changed sides when the case went to the U.S.  
Supreme Court, saying there should not be a blanket rule when it 
comes to what is best for a child. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are probably going to be some instances when it's not in  
the best interest of siblings to be together,'' Ms. Carli said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo was placed in foster care three days after he was born. He  
may have been injured by the cocaine his mother used while 
pregnant, according to court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	The foster mother had both Gloria and Hugo for the past two  
years, identified in court papers as ``Enid,'' wanted to keep both 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hugo's father believed the boy would be better off with the  
New Jersey aunt, who has raised her own special-needs child. The 
aunt has not sought custody of Gloria. 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Drogin, who represents the father, said the family is  
thrilled and relieved the court battle finally seems to be over. 
</P>
<P>
	After Hugo and Gloria were separated in January, the two  
families said they would try to work out a visitation agreement. 
Ms. Drogin said the siblings have not seen each other, but speak on 
the phone once a week and Hugo ``has been doing very well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
