<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Get Last Chance for Peace  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- With NATO missiles and warplanes  
poised to strike, a U.S. envoy began a last bid today to persuade 
Yugoslavia's president to accept a Kosovo peace plan and the 
thousands of foreign troops that would enforce it. Richard 
Holbrooke held four hours of talks with President Slobodan 
Milosevic this evening. A brief report on Serbian television gave 
no indication of any breakthrough. Further consultations were 
expected early tomorrow, the White House said. Meanwhile, fighting 
raged today between government forces and the rebel Kosovo 
Liberation Army in Kosovo. Several villages were ablaze and there 
were unconfirmed reports of mass killings near the town of Srbica. 

</P>
<P>
	Body Identified As Missing Sightseer  
</P>
<P>
	SIERRA VILLAGE, Calif. (AP) -- One of the two burned bodies found  
in the trunk of a charred rental car was identified today as one of 
three sightseers who disappeared during a trip to Yosemite National 
Park. The FBI used dental records to identify the body of Carole 
Sund, 42. Officials said they may use DNA testing to identify the 
other victim in the trunk. Mrs. Sund disappeared five weeks ago 
with her 15-year-old daughter and a family friend. 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian Defends Himself in Trial  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian went on trial on murder  
charges today. Acting as his own lawyer, told the jury that like an 
executioner, he was merely carrying out his professional duty in a 
videotaped suicide shown on ``60 Minutes.'' Kevorkian was charged 
after he gave a lethal injection to a patient with Lou Gehrig's 
disease. In his opening statement, Kevorkian said he acted out of 
compassion for 52-year-old Thomas Youk and was no more culpable 
than an executioner. Kevorkian will be allowed to consult with his 
lawyers during the trial but said that defending himself was ``what 
I've planned all along.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Four Dead in Alaska Avalanche  
</P>
<P>
	TURNAGAIN PASS, Alaska (AP) -- Volunteers recovered two more  
bodies today from an avalanche that swept through a popular 
snowmobiling spot yesterday, raising the death toll to four. As 
many as seven other people were missing. About 85 volunteers moved 
shoulder-to-shoulder with poles today, probing for bodies in areas 
where witnesses had reported seeing snowmobilers disappear or where 
machines had been discovered. Police have also asked the military 
for 200 people to help in the search. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Rules on Rights of Teen-Agers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Handling two disputes over the rights of  
teen-agers and parents, the Supreme Court today allowed a city to 
continue imposing a nighttime curfew, but barred two high schools 
from requiring drug tests for all students suspended for 
disciplinary reasons. A nighttime curfew for minors has never been 
fully reviewed by the nation's highest court. Today's action may 
encourage other communities to consider adopting similar 
ordinances. The court's denial of review in the drug-testing case, 
meanwhile, is likely only to confuse the already murky legal status 
of student drug-testing. 

</P>
<P>
	Cyclone Pounds Australian Coast  
</P>
<P>
	PERTH, Australia (AP) -- Destructive winds and heavy rain  
battered western Australia Tuesday as the powerful cyclone that has 
flattened scores of homes and downed power lines continued its 
inland march. A man who had refused to evacuate the area near where 
Cyclone Vance made its landfall was missing and presumed dead. 
There were no other immediate reports of casualties. As it moved 
inland, Vance was considered exceptionally dangerous with winds of 
140 mph. 

</P>
<P>
	TV Show Helps Find Vietnam MIAs  
</P>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Callers to a television show called ``In  
Search of Comrades in Arms'' have helped find the remains of 300 
Vietnamese missing since the Vietnam War. Col. Chi Phan, head of 
television programming for the army, said today the remains were 
located by officials based on 4,000 tips from viewers. The program, 
which began airing in 1993, runs 10 times a week. Each episode of 
the program is five minutes long and gives the names, birth dates 
and pictures of missing fighters. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices advanced in early trading  
Tuesday on buying by foreign investors. The Nikkei rose 13.88 
points to 16,392.66 points. On Wall Street, the Dow lost 13.04 to 
close at 9,890.51. The Nasdaq ended down 25.35 at 2,395.92. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Gets No. 1 Ranking Back  
</P>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Pete Sampras reclaimed the No. 1  
tennis ranking he relinquished last week, winning his match today 
at the Lipton Championships while Carlos Moya lost. Sampras beat 
Albert Costa 6-4, 6-4. Top-ranked Moya lost to Sebastien Grosjean, 
3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (11-9). The results ensure that Sampras will return 
to No. 1 when the new rankings are released. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
