<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Oscarcast: Long, Dull and Tacky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There's an old saying that no one ever left the  
theater humming the scenery. But if there was anything about the 
Oscarcast worth singing about, it was the set. 
</P>
<P>
	That, and Roberto Benigni. In fact, among mere mortals on hand  
Sunday, the excitable, ecstatic writer-director-star of ``Life Is 
Beautiful'' was almost the sole salvation of ``The 71st Annual 
Academy Awards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Could this year's telecast have been any duller? Only if the  
Italian superstar hadn't been on hand to accept two Oscars in his 
rapid-fire, euphoric broken English. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to kiss everybody,'' he exalted after stepping from  
seat-back to seat-back to reach the stage for his best foreign 
language film trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	A little while later, the Oscarcast got another welcome jolt  
when Benigni returned to claim the best actor award: ``I would like 
to be Jupiter and kidnap everybody,'' he bubbled, ``and lie down in 
the firmament making love with everybody!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who knows what would have gone on had he won a third?  
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the broadcast, which ABC aired live from Los Angeles'  
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion, was rated ZZZ. And that couldn't all be 
blamed on its record-breaking length: 4 hours, 2 minutes. The show 
was just dull. 
</P>
<P>
	The setting sure wasn't, though. Did it look like a rotunda  
dome? A lunar module? A huge, glorious umbrella? It was all that 
and more. It had far more excitement than most of the stars with 
which it shared the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Dull? Even the drama surrounding Elia Kazan's life achievement  
award thudded to an anticlimax. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than anybody, he inspired us,'' said Robert De Niro three  
long hours into the broadcast. De Niro had joined director Martin 
Scorsese to present the award, an object of bitter debate between 
admirers of the great director and those who denounced him for 
naming colleagues four decades ago in a government investigation of 
communist influence on Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank you all very much,'' said the 89-year-old Kazan. ``I  
think I can just slip away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that was that.  
</P>
<P>
	In her third turn as host, Whoopi Goldberg had little new to  
offer. Hers was the same tacky, self-satisfied display she had 
visited on the Oscarcast before. 
</P>
<P>
	Her appearances in various Oscar-related costumes, beginning  
with the finery of Queen Elizabeth (not to mention her wearing 
white-face), should have been funny. But Goldberg has a fixation on 
bodily functions and rude double entendres that reduces her act to 
the level of a naughty 8-year-old. 
</P>
<P>
	Early on, she made a pun on ``we ... we.'' Later on, she made a  
pun about leaks. Observing that William Shakespeare has had a good 
year at the movies, she purred suggestively, ``Little Willie is 
very large.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After one of such wisecracks, Goldberg made a cackling reference  
to past Oscarcast host Billy Crystal. ``You're missin' Billy just 
about now -- aincha?'' 
</P>
<P>
	If you only knew, Whoopi.  
</P>
<P>
	What became an Oscar snoozefest had begun promisingly with its  
first award, best supporting actor. It went to James Coburn for 
``Affliction.'' But instead of rising to the occasion, the veteran 
actor, a sentimental favorite after some 70 films without so much 
as a nomination, slowed things to a crawl with his laundry list of 
thank-yous. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually surefire, presenters Robin Williams and Chris Rock were  
each downright listless. 
</P>
<P>
	And as for the dance number showcasing nominated musical scores:  
It was nice to look at, but Savion Glover tap-dancing to a theme 
from ``Saving Private Ryan''? What was up with that?! 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, Gwyneth Paltrow's sobbingly grateful acceptance of her  
best actress Oscar for ``Shakespeare in Love'' was memorable. 
</P>
<P>
	And four separate farewell tributes -- including those for Roy  
Rogers, Frank Sinatra and director Stanley Kubrick -- were each 
moving. Oscar knows how to say goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, could Oscar say goodbye to Whoopi Goldberg as host? And  
before next year, maybe hire that funny, never-dull Roberto 
Benigni! 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
