<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AmWest Seeks To Lure Travelers Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Now that America West Airlines and its flight  
attendants have made peace with one another, they can begin the 
process of making peace with the airline's customers. 
</P>
<P>
	America West averted a strike last weekend by reaching an $80  
million settlement with the Association of Flight Attendants. For 
days, both sides had been threatening one another in a labor 
dispute that could have stranded 100,000 passengers during the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Longman, an analyst at Arnhold &AMP; S. Bleichroedoer in New  
York, said Monday the airline would probably have to make things up 
to its business travelers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest problem has been over the last two weeks because  
business travelers have booked away. Clearly, they will have to put 
out some inducements to business travelers,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those inducements could include free frequent-flier miles, seat  
upgrades or a fare sale -- though Longman said a sale at the 
nation's ninth-largest carrier would likely be confined to the 
Phoenix area and not go nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	America West, based in suburban Tempe, has hubs here, in Las  
Vegas and Columbus, Ohio, serving 53 domestic destinations and 
eight cities in Mexico and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Patty Nowack, a spokeswoman for the airline, refused to comment  
on what the company might do to woo travelers back. 
</P>
<P>
	But at least one airline analyst, Michael Boyd of the Boyd  
Group, said America West won't have to do anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``The minute the press release went out saying 'We have a  
settlement,' customers put it behind them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the sides reached an agreement before a strike, America  
West didn't sustain any significant damage, Boyd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Longman said America West chairman William Franke would need to  
do some public relations repair with investors, though. Franke 
himself acknowledged as much, saying after the agreement that ``we 
need to focus on the customer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	America West's history of tumultuous labor relations, both with  
the flight attendants and the mechanics group with which it reached 
agreement in October, has pushed down the value of the company's 
stock, Longman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bill Franke is going to want to spend some more time on  
investor relations,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deanna Clarkson, a spokeswoman for the flight attendant's union,  
said she was cautiously optimistic that the agreement reached 
Friday would begin a new era of relations between the airline and 
its flight attendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the feud that led to last week's strike countdown began  
years ago. Employees at the carrier took a 10 percent pay cut to 
help the company recover after it filed for bankruptcy in 1991. The 
pay was not restored even though the company posted record profits 
in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had (Franke) given us a few extra bucks and a pat on the back  
and acknowledged the work we do a few years back, he has no idea 
what that would have done,'' Clarkson said. 
</P>
<P>
	That Franke showed up in person for the last several hours of  
the contract negotiations and shook hands with union 
representatives made a major difference, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that kind of respect continues outside those doors, I think  
that can be the beginning of a different sort of relationship,'' 
Clarkson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract, which union leaders hope will be ratified by  
members in the next 20 to 30 days, includes a pay raise. Top-paid 
flight attendants will see their salary rise from $23,800 to 
between $33,000 and $37,000. That's about 80 percent to 90 percent 
of the $41,200 paid by rival Southwest Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase would lift America West flight attendants from the  
bottom of the top-10 carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight attendants would also get a ``per diem'' for the  
first time -- an extra payment for every hour they are on the job or 
awaiting a flight to their home base. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
