<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cabletron To Sell Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Cabletron Systems will sell its  
manufacturing division to Canada's Celestica Inc., which will make 
Cabletron's computer networking products in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear how many of Cabletron's 5,900 jobs  
would be lost. The move would save Cabletron $50 million in the 
first year, the company said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects to reduce its work force by about 900  
employees over the next nine months. It plans to close its Ironton, 
Ohio, plant and lay off 300 workers there. About 600 employees at 
the Rochester plant being bought by Celestica will be laid off by 
Cabletron and rehired by Celestica, Cabletron spokesman Darren 
Orzechowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the biggest driving factors behind doing this is we  
were able to partner with a company that's committed to New 
Hampshire,'' he said. ``We expect that almost all of the 
(Rochester) employees ... will be offered positions by Celistica.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Celestica already has a plant in Exeter. Workers there and in  
Rochester will be moved to a new plant Celestica plans to build in 
Portsmouth within the next 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Celestica, which is based in North York, Ontario, has 14,000  
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate announcement, Cabletron said its loss in the  
fourth quarter of its fiscal year ended Feb. 28 narrowed to $8.25 
million, or 5 cents a share, from $263.4 million, or $1.67 a share, 
a year earlier. Sales rose to $345.1 million from $311.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	For the full fiscal year, the company's loss widened to $240  
million, or $1.43 a share, on $1.41 billion in sales from a loss of 
$127.1 million, or 81 cents a share, on $1.38 billion in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabletron has lost market share to key competitors, including  
3Com Corp. and Cisco Systems Inc. It laid off a total of 780 
employees in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Several high-ranking personnel changes and delays entering new  
markets prompted speculation earlier this year that the company 
might be bought. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabletron recently has tried to narrow its focus to  
data-networking equipment for corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Celestica has a full range of advanced manufacturing services  
that we will leverage to our competitive advantage,'' John 
d'Auguste, Cabletron's president of operations, said in a statement 
announcing the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugene Polistuk, president and chief executive officer of  
Celestica, said the move would allow his company to expand into the 
networking industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was announced after markets closed. Cabletron rose 31 1/4  
cents to close at $10.06 1/4 a share on the New York Stock Exchange, 
where Celestica fell 37 1/2 cents to close at $27.43 3/4. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
