<HEADLINE> Court Orders Gucci, LVMH To Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A Dutch court ruled Monday that  
fashion group Gucci NV must negotiate with French luxury goods 
maker LVMH Moet Hennessey Louis Vuitton over LVMH's $7.86 billion 
hostile takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The court in Holland, where Gucci is based, also upheld an  
agreement between Gucci and French retailer 
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute in which PPR will take a 40 percent 
interest in the company. But the court suspended any parts of the 
agreement which would hamper the negotiations between Gucci and 
LVMH. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges also said Gucci's current management and supervisory  
board would have to enter negotiations with LVMH, meaning PPR won't 
be able to install any new members on Gucci's board, as planned 
under the original agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The court also restores LVMH's voting rights on its 26 percent  
stake in the Italian luxury goods maker, which had been suspended 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Gucci had said earlier Monday it was seriously considering the  
$81-a-share offer from LVMH. The French group's offer, made Sunday, 
includes the shares in Gucci that are owned by PPR. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian firm expanded its capital by 40 percent last week to  
ward off what has become a hostile acquisition attempt by LVMH. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case heard Monday in Amsterdam, LVMH was trying to  
overturn defensive moves made by Gucci earlier this year which made 
it difficult for LVMH to gain a majority of the company's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Gucci issued about 37 million shares to its  
employees to deter an earlier bid from the French company. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Gucci rose sharply Monday as investors speculated that  
LVMH will increase the $81-a-share offer or that another company 
will make a counter-bid. The stock closed at 73.70 euros ($80.35) 
per share on the Amsterdam Stock Exchange, an increase of 10 
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
