<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Six Skaters Make 4-Revolution Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) - There were quads in the air and on the  
ice and it was just the qualifying rounds at the World Figure 
Skating Championships today. 
</P>
<P>
	Six skaters completed the four-revolution jump, the most ever in  
a competition and American Tim Goebel became the first skater to 
land a quad salchow in the world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond the jumps, the real jockeying for positions began today  
the Russians leading the way as expected. Yevgeny Plushenko won one 
group and defending world champion Alexei Yagudin won the other, 
despite a sore left leg. 
</P>
<P>
	American champion Michael Weiss came in second to Plushenko and  
former Olympic champion Alexei Urmanov was second to Yagudin. 
</P>
<P>
	Later today the pairs have their short programs. Russians Yelena  
Berezhnaya and Anton Sikarulidze are the defending world champions 
and hope to rebound from recent poor performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday, in the men's qualifying, the quads came in quantity and  
quality, 
</P>
<P>
	Plushenko, Elvis Stojko, Weiss, Goebel, Guo Zhengxin of China  
and Anthony Liu of Australia hit them, marking the most in a single 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, three different skaters did them at the 1997 Grand  
Prix final -- future Olympic champion Ilya Kulik, Urmanov and Stojko 
hit them. Stojko and two others hit them at the 1997 world 
championships finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss finally nailed a clean quad toe loop. In 1997 he thought  
he had one but the videotape replay hours later showed he had 
slightly two-footed it. There was no doubt about it Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I initially wasn't planning on trying it but as soon as I saw  
two of them hit theirs out there, I knew if I wanted to be up there 
in first or second I had to go for it, '' he said. ``It worked 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss also did triple-triple combinations and three other triple  
jumps, but fell on his second triple axel attempt. Still that put 
him ahead of Stojko, pushing the three-time world champion to third 
in the qualifying group 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko hit his first quad but fell on his second. ``I think I  
was just a little sloppy on the landing,'' Stojko said of his brush 
with the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	He found the qualifications, which count in the scoring this  
year, difficult to adjust to. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very hard to do at this point -- to give everything or  
hold back,'' said Stojko, who turned 27 Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He also didn't do any triple-triple combinations.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew the triple-triples would make the difference,'' said  
Weiss, who had marks between 5.6 and 5.8 but, more importantly, the 
advantage over Stojko with five of the second judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Plushenko started strong, with his quad but had slight errors on  
a number of his other jumps. Nonetheless, he ranked ahead of Weiss 
on all but the Swiss judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Yagudin, who has been consistent throughout the season and  
delivered an awesome quad and quad-triple in practice the day 
before, won his group easily without even attempting one. 
</P>
<P>
	His marks were nearly all 5.8s and 5.9s.  
</P>
<P>
	He did eight triples in doing just enough to get into first  
without putting additional pressure on a sore left calf muscle that 
caused him to shake his leg as soon as he finished. 
</P>
<P>
	Goebel came in fifth helped by his quad salchow. In contrast to  
the toe loops, which the other skaters did, the salchow does not 
have use the skate's toe pick to help pole-vault the skater up. 
</P>
<P>
	Goebel started slowly, putting two hands down on a triple axel.  
Then he got up and landed the quad salchow, which he had done 
previously at the Goodwill Games and junior Grand Prix finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The qualifying round advances 15 skaters from each group and  
counts for 20 percent of the total score. 
</P>
<P>
	The short program accounts for an additional 30 with Thursday's  
long program counting the remaining 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
