<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Auto Dealers Going Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Two Internet auto sellers are going  
public with stock sales this week as shoppers on the virtual 
highway begin to usurp neighborhood car dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was able to get two cars online last year without having to  
go down to a dealership and haggle,'' said Linda Hill of Lafayette, 
Calif. ``It made the process a lot simpler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, more than 2 million consumers used the Internet to  
research their new-car purchases. A report from Forrester Research 
Inc., predicts that by 2003 nearly 8 million new-car purchases will 
be influenced by the Internet and nearly half a million new cars 
will be purchased entirely online. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rise of online car buying will radically alter the  
automobile and retailing landscape,'' said James L. McQuivey, a 
senior analyst at Forrester. ``Some of these changes will be 
wrenching, as manufacturers rethink their role. Other changes will 
come more naturally, like the increased emphasis on customer 
service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This new way of shopping is spawning a thriving online auto  
sales business. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet-based purchasing services Autoweb.com and Autobytel.com  
have been so successful they are both are planning initial stock 
sales this week -- Autoweb on Tuesday and Autobytel on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Santa Clara-based Autoweb.com Inc. plans to sell 5 million  
shares at $10 to $12, raising about $55 million. Autobytel.com 
plans to sell 4.5 million shares at $16 to $18, raising about $76.5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies, along with Microsoft Carpoint, lead the  
online auto sales market. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's how it works: A carbuyer points and clicks their way  
through a Web site to submit an online request of the make and 
model they want to buy. Then the online car dealers connect the 
customer with an accredited dealership, which e-mails or calls the 
customer within 24 hours with a non negotiable and supposedly rock 
bottom offer. The customer can then go to the dealership and buy 
their car. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford University's Graduate School of Business recently  
released an auto industry research report that concludes that the 
Internet is shaking up the $1 trillion auto market. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were surprised by the way such a staid industry is  
completely revolutionizing itself in such a short time,'' said 
graduate student Jorge Borbolla, who worked on the study. 
</P>
<P>
	The study found that the increased online commerce could shrink  
the number of dealers in the United States from 22,000 to 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But Glen Reiken, fleet manager at Almaden Mazda in San Jose,  
said he's not worried about becoming obsolete. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they're looking at on the web, a picture on a computer,  
is not touching, feeling, tasting, like they get when the come in 
and test drive,'' he said. ``At a dealership, customers get the 
same price as online and they get to have a relationship with the 
seller as well. That's important.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
