<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Pilgrims Begin Mecca Rituals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Muslim pilgrims clothed in white  
began the ritual circling of the sacred Kaaba stone structure 
Monday in the holy city of Mecca. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kaaba, an ancient cubic structure in Mecca's Grand Mosque,  
is Islam's holiest site. Believed to date to the time of the 
prophet Abraham, the Kaaba has been covered with a new black cloth 
that is richly embroidered. 
</P>
<P>
	As Muslims from around the world converged for the start of the  
pilgrimage, or hajj, on Friday, Saudi Arabia said it was ready to 
help and protect the estimated 2 million people expected to arrive. 
</P>
<P>
	About 35,000 police, national guardsmen and volunteers were  
dispersed to keep watch over the pilgrims during the rituals, which 
last about two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, ambulances and medical centers have been readied to  
deal with emergencies. Stampedes or fires at past pilgrimages have 
killed hundreds and sent hundreds of others to clinics and 
hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, some pilgrims are overcome with emotion and need medical  
help. Others succumb to temperatures that can exceed 97 degrees 
during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Grand Mosque, when loudspeakers blared the midday call to  
prayer, the procession around the Kaaba ground to a peaceful halt. 
Pilgrims paused to listen to verses from the Koran, Islam's holy 
book, and join in prayers. 
</P>
<P>
	Other pilgrims, unable to make it into the mosque because of the  
crowds, prayed outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohammed Zayed, a 32-year-old man from India, said that  
participating in a pilgrimage was exhilarating. ``As soon as I saw 
the Haram (Grand Mosque), I had goose bumps,'' he said. ``My tears 
flowed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims are required to make the hajj at least once in a  
lifetime, if they can afford it. 
</P>
<P>
	George Tomasevich, 56, from Middletown, N.J., said he was  
astounded by the spirituality of Mecca. 
</P>
<P>
	``Truly, this is the original home of God,'' said Tomasevich,  
who converted to Islam last November. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the 2 million people expected will come from  
abroad, the rest from inside the kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, about 180 pilgrims died when a stampede broke out as  
pilgrims were performing the ``stoning the devil'' ritual. A 
similar stampede in 1994 left 270 dead. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1997 pilgrimage, fires driven by high winds tore  
through a sprawling, overcrowded tent city at Mina outside Mecca, 
trapping and killing more than 340 pilgrims and injuring 1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia has since installed fireproof tents, increased the  
numbers of rescue vehicles and provided safer stoves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
