<HEADLINE> Dow Dips, Nasdaq Sees Lift / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed today, as investors searched  
for direction after the Dow Jones industrial average repeatedly 
tried without success to close above 10,000 last week. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was off 1.67 at 9,901.88.  
</P>
<P>
	But broader stock indicators were higher, with the Nasdaq  
composite up 6.48 at 2,427.75, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index 
up 0.63 at 1,299.92. 
</P>
<P>
	No fresh economic figures were released this morning. Interest  
rates dipped on the bond market, with yields on 30-year Treasury 
bonds slipping to 5.54 percent in early trading from 5.55 percent 
late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was continuing its Dow 10,000 watch after several  
nail-biting sessions last week, when the blue-chip index climbed 
numerous times above the five-digit number on an intraday basis but 
failed to close there. On Friday, the Dow got as high as 10,085.31, 
then skidded as earnings estimates for IBM were lowered. It dropped 
94.07 to close at 9,903.55 and broader indexes also fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow did manage two record closing highs last week, the  
second one on Thurday at 9,997.62. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 did 
the same, closing at a high on Thursday at 1,316.55. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, technology shares were again disappointing, with  
IBM down 1 1/8 at 167 7/16, and Dell down 2 at 38 1/4. Declining issues 
edged out advancers by 1,118 to 1,114 on the New York Stock 
Exchange, where volume came to 82.81 million shares in the first 
half hour, lower than Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas markets, the Japan's stock market was closed for a  
holiday. In afternoon trading in Europe, all eyes were on U.S. 
markets. Germany's DAX index was off 0.99 percent, Britain's FT-SE 
100 was flat, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.41 percent. 



</P>
</TEXT>
