<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Hear Trial Attendance Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether prosecutors violate defendants' rights by implying that 
their attendance at trial lets them tailor their testimony to fit 
the evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear New York prosecutors' argument that  
such comments to a jury do not burden defendants' constitutional 
right to be present at trial and confront the witnesses against 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Agard of Queens was convicted in 1991 of sodomy and weapons  
possession, and sentenced to 10 to 20 years in prison. He testified 
in his own defense at his New York state court trial. 
</P>
<P>
	During closing arguments, a prosecutor told jurors that unlike  
other witnesses, Agard was allowed to be in court and hear all the 
other testimony before he testified. 
</P>
<P>
	``That gives you a big advantage, doesn't it?'' the prosecutor  
said. ``You get to sit here and think, `What am I going to say? ... 
How am I going to fit it into the evidence?''' 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge turned down Agard's appeal, but the 2nd U.S.  
Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the prosecutor's argument 
violated his rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor ``cast suspicion upon the defendant's unique  
Sixth Amendment right to be present at his trial and hear all 
testimony'' as well as his Fifth Amendment right to testify in his 
own defense, the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	Such an argument might be allowed if it were based on factual  
elements of a defendant's testimony, the appeals court said. But it 
said a prosecutor cannot make a general attack on a defendant's 
credibility because he exercised his right to attend his trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, prosecutors said the 2nd Circuit  
court's ruling was an improper extension of a 1965 Supreme Court 
decision that said prosecutors cannot comment in court on a 
defendant's exercise of his right not to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	Agard's lawyers said the 2nd Circuit court did not create a  
rigid rule but said the propriety of such comments by prosecutors 
would depend on a case's facts. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Portuondo vs. Agard, 98-1170.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
