<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil-Price Crisis Hits Saudis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- For Saudi Arabia, the world's  
largest oil exporter, last year's sharp drop in oil prices was an 
economic catastrophe. 
</P>
<P>
	The kingdom's oil revenues shrank to $30 billion -- a drop of $20  
billion from the year before -- and plunged its budget deeply into 
deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Government hiring has been frozen, construction projects have  
been shelved and foreign military contracts are being rescheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank has had to intervene at least once, and  
possibly twice, to keep speculators from forcing the depreciation 
of the Saudi currency, the riyal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been our warning, our wake-up call,'' said Mohammed  
Tunisi, editor of the financial daily Al-Eqtisadiah. ``If we learn 
the lessons, it gives me hope for the coming century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most important lesson, experts say, is that Saudi Arabia has  
to diversify its economy so that it's not at the mercy of the ups 
and downs of world oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Taecker, chief economist at the Saudi American Bank, said  
that even if OPEC production cuts under discussion in Austria this 
week boost prices, ``it doesn't change the fact that Saudi Arabia 
has to stay focused on economic policies that promote 
diversification.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's easier said than done in a country which has one-quarter  
of the world's oil reserves -- 260 billion barrels -- and has been 
dependent on that one commodity for the past five decades. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also difficult because the kingdom's 20 million people have  
become used to government largesse that includes free education and 
health care, subsidized utilities, low-interest housing loans and 
guaranteed jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet because of the oil crunch, once-unthinkable reforms are  
being discussed openly, including limiting the monthly stipends 
that go to the royal family's 7,000 princes and princesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am against having salaries for the royal family,'' said  
Prince Alwaleed bin Talal, a billionaire entrepreneur who is a 
grandson of the late King Abdel-Aziz, the founder of modern Saudi 
Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no sign yet that royal stipends are being reduced. But  
Crown Prince Abdullah, who has managed day-to-day operations in the 
kingdom since King Fahd suffered a stroke in 1995, reportedly has 
ordered scofflaw princes to make good on water, electricity and 
phone bills that they have long ignored or face cutoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Confronted with a budget deficit of $12 billion this year for  
the second year in a row, the government also is being forced to go 
ahead at long last with reforms that have been on the drawing board 
for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Electricity and telephone utilities are being privatized, and  
customers already have been warned to expect significant rate hikes 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia also is moving to encourage private business. A  
long-discussed investment law is expected to be adopted this 
summer, and a capital markets act should follow, ministers say. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdullah Dabbagh, adviser to the Council of Saudi Chambers of  
Commerce and Industry, said one aim is to get Saudis to bring home 
the estimated $420 billion they have stashed outside their 
homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way to get this money and foreign money is to open  
new venues to investment,'' said Dabbagh, who also is a member of 
the kingdom's advisory Consultative Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the ``new'' investors could be big American oil companies  
that lost their holdings in Saudi Arabia in the 1970s when the 
country nationalized the oil-producing Aramco. 
</P>
<P>
	At the invitation of Abdullah, U.S. oil companies already have  
begun discussing proposals -- not for oil exploration but for 
development of the kingdom's vast natural gas fields and industries 
that use gas, including petrochemicals and fertilizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
