<DOCNO> APW19990322.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 22:31:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Direct Chemo Can Extend Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Injecting chemotherapy directly into a  
tumor and cutting off its blood supply can double the survival rate 
of adults with colon cancer that has spread to the liver, a medical 
researcher says. 
</P>
<P>
	In a study of 51 patients at the University of Pennsylvania  
Medical Center, those treated with the technique survived an 
average of two years -- twice as long as those undergoing systemic 
chemotherapy, in which cancer-killing drugs are delivered into the 
bloodstream. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least we've bought them some time,'' said Dr. Michael  
Soulen, the lead researcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was presented in Orlando at the 24th Annual Scientific  
Meeting of the Society of Cardiovascular and Interventional 
Radiology. There were 51 patients in the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Jack Wands, a liver research expert at Brown University,  
called the study provocative but said it needs to be expanded to a 
larger group of people before any conclusions can be made. 
</P>
<P>
	Colon cancer is the third most common fatal cancer in the United  
States, with about 150,000 new cases a year. Half of those patients 
die when cancer spreads to the liver and becomes difficult to 
treat. 
</P>
<P>
	In the study, the patients underwent the treatment known as  
chemoembolization. A nick the size of a pencil tip is made in the 
patient's groin and a catheter is placed in an artery. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors then inject chemotherapy that is 20 to 200 times  
stronger than what is used for systemic chemotherapy. Plastic 
particles are used to block the artery, cutting off about 25 
percent of the liver's blood supply. 
</P>
<P>
	Choking the tumor's energy source prevents the tumor from  
washing out the chemotherapy, and blocking the artery keeps the 
poison in the tumor, Soulen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Side effects from systemic chemotherapy, such as hair loss and  
mouth sores, also are significantly reduced in chemoembolization, 
Soulen said. The procedure, however, can cause liver damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to systemic chemo, it's much more comfortable,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two to four more years of trial studies using a broader  
population are needed before the technique can be considered for 
popular treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
