<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Gov't Wants To Cut Salaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Faced with declining revenues and  
spiraling costs, Thailand's government wants to cut bureaucrats' 
salaries and eventually trim their ranks, a government spokesman 
said on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Akaphol Sorasuchart said government salaries were eating up more  
than 50 percent of Thailand's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should not be more than 40 percent,'' he said. ``In the  
short term, we would like to cut salaries. In the long term, we 
would like to reduce the number of government officials, to 
restructure the government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He gave no specific targets for the reductions.  
</P>
<P>
	Thailand is in the midst of its worst economic crisis in modern  
times and is receiving a $17.2 billion bailout from the 
International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	As personal and corporate incomes drop and more people lose  
their jobs, Thailand's tax revenues have fallen, putting a serious 
dent in the nation's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF recently approved deficit spending of 6 percent of gross  
domestic product for the Thai government. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers will hurt the most by the budget shortfall, Akaphol  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farmers are suffering even more this year because, aside from  
the unemployed migrating back to their families in rural areas and 
increasing the burden on many families, prices for farm goods are 
dropping,'' Akaphol said. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers account for about 60 percent of Thailand's population.  
The country also has a large number of people who migrate to the 
cities in search of work during good times, and return to the 
farmlands when work is scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	``The focus of the government's budget in the coming year will  
be aimed at solving social problems, especially in rural areas. 
That is our priority,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Akaphol said, however, that the government would have to seek  
new loans from international agencies to be able to meet its goal 
of helping the rural poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
