<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Longtime AP Reporter Dies at 84 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- J.D. Holmes, an Associated Press reporter  
who covered Montana state government for 30 years, died Sunday. He 
was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes covered the Legislature from 1948 until 1978. He was  
known for the depth of his knowledge of state government; even 
legislators relied on his notes and math to be sure the state 
budget was in balance. 
</P>
<P>
	He covered 16 regular and six special sessions of the  
Legislature for the AP. One of the special sessions was necessary 
when Holmes discovered a major mistake in an appropriations bill 
after legislators had gone home. 
</P>
<P>
	State representatives in 1991 honored Holmes with a resolution  
recognizing his ``high standards and personal dedication.'' He was 
honored in a packed legislative chamber after being formally 
escorted to the well of the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Rep. Francis Bardanouve, a longtime Appropriations  
Committee chairman, said Holmes ``knew more about how much money we 
spent than we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He was meticulous in preparation,'' Bardanouve said. ``I  
recognized him as a very careful student of the Legislature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After his retirement, Holmes returned to the Legislature to  
lobby for Montana artists until 1983. He ran unsuccessfully in 1981 
for the Helena City Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	As a reporter, Holmes began each day methodically clipping  
articles about government and politics from several newspapers. His 
clippings eventually filled 71 file drawers, and Holmes and his 
family were worried that the upstairs floor in their home would 
collapse from the weight. 
</P>
<P>
	After he retired, Holmes donated his records to the Montana  
Historical Society, where they still are used for reference. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes, whose initials stood for Joseph Defrees, joined the AP  
in Helena after several years as managing editor of the Lewistown 
Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, he owned or operated three weekly newspapers -- the  
Sweet Grass News at Big Timber, the Yellowstonian at West 
Yellowstone and the Fergus County Argus at Lewistown. He also 
worked for newspapers in Sheridan, Wyo., and Wichita, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, two daughters and a son.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
